1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d4 {A very principled move. White strikes first in the centre, which is the reason why in most lines of this chapter, Black is somewhat short of space.} ({Equally good are} 3. g3) ({and} 3. Nc3) (3. b3 $5 {will be analysed in later chapters of this training camp as an alternative for the "lazy" player, who prefers to avoid all Symmetrical English theory.}) 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 {Now Black has a large number of reasonable options:} g6 {In the Maroczy, Black has the choice between three different ideas: 1) Play Nxd4 early and force White to take back with the queen. This is usually connected with plans based on the pawn break b7-b5.2) Delay Nxd4 and force White to take back with the bishop. After this, Black usually tries to exchange this bishop and play for a dark-square blockade on the queenside. 3) Exchange the f6-knight for the one on d4 by playing an early Ng4. As a consequence, Black has more dark-square control but less control over d5.} (4... e6 5. Nc3 Bb4 6. Qb3 (6. g3 {transposes to the highly theoretical Nimzo-Indian with g2-g3.}) 6... Bc5 ({Other moves give up the pair of bishops for no compensation:} 6... Nc6 $6 7. Nxc6 Bxc3+ 8. Qxc3 $14) (6... Qa5 $6 7. Bd2 $14 {, followed by Nc2.}) 7. Nf3 {, and for example} O-O 8. Bg5 Be7 9. e3 b6 10. Be2 Bb7 11. O-O d6 12. Rfd1 Nbd7 13. Rac1 a6 14. Qc2 Qc7 15. b3 {If Black doesn't do anything drastic like a premature d6-d5, the game will slowly transpose into a Hedgehog-type position.}) (4... b6 5. Nc3 Bb7 {The main idea of this move-order is to keep White from achieving quick development with e4, f4 and Bd3, followed by dangerous play on the kingside.} 6. f3 ({Also playable is} 6. Bg5) 6... e6 ({Black can also opt for a mix between the Hedgehog and the Maroczy:} 6... g6 7. e4 d6 8. Be3 Bg7 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Rc1 Rc8 12. Qd2 a6 {Unless White plays with a bishop on g2, this double-fianchetto is generally considered slightly inferior. Sooner or later, White will play Nd5, and, after Nxd5 or Bxd5, take back with the c-pawn. After this, the weakness created by b7-b6 becomes a problem, as the c6 square can be used by White's minor pieces and rooks.}) 7. e4 d6 8. Be3 Nbd7 9. Qb3 {The more aggressive option. White prepares long castling and kingside play.} (9. Be2 {With this relatively quiet move, White prepares short castling. This is followed by play on the queenside, usually connected with a2-a4-a5 at some point, to create weaknesses in Black's structure.}) 9... a6 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Kb1 Be7 12. g4 {White simply pushes his kingside pawns, and it is not easy for Black to generate counterplay.}) (4... Nc6 5. Nc3 e6 6. a3 {Prophylaxis against Bb4, which would be Black's response to the otherwise desirable 6.e4. Black would like to prove that 6.a3 is a loss of time, but this is not so easy. White's control of the b4-square is generally useful, as it not only stabilises White's knight on c3 but also provides some extra safety for his king, which will remain uncastled for at least a few more moves. Now Black has three reasonable options:} ({Also good but heavily analysed is} 6. g3 Qb6) 6... Be7 (6... Bc5 7. Nb3 Bb6 (7... Be7 8. e4 d6 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O b6 11. Bf4 $1 Bb7 12. Rc1 Ne5 13. Nd2 $14 {This is identical to the 6...Be7 line, but with an extra tempo for White.}) 8. c5 Bc7 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bh4 O-O 11. e3 {Black will sooner or later have to play b7-b6 or d7-d5, to get rid of the cramping pawn on c5.} b6 (11... d5 12. cxd6 Qxd6 13. Qxd6 Bxd6 $14) 12. Rc1 bxc5 13. Nxc5 d5 14. Be2 {Black's central majority cannot move without becoming weak and his minor pieces on the c-file are vulnerable to ideas like Nb5.}) (6... d5 {offers White a small but stable and risk-free advantage after} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 ({or play against Black's IQP after} 7... exd5 8. Bg5 ({or} 8. Bf4)) 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Bd2 $14 {, followed by e2-e4.}) 7. e4 {Another Hedgehog type position is reached in which White's space advantage offers him good chances to play for an advantage.} O-O 8. Nf3 {Preventing d7-d5.} d6 9. Be2 b6 10. O-O Bb7 11. Bf4 Rc8 12. Rc1 Ne5 13. Nd2 {White enjoys a considerable space advantage and he can slowly improve his position. At the same time, it is not easy for Black to realise any pawn breaks.}) (4... e5 {This move introduces an interesting pawn sacrifice, that, however, doesn't fully equalise for Black.} 5. Nb5 d5 6. cxd5 Bc5 7. N5c3 O-O 8. g3 {The modern way to play this position, and considered the critical test for Black's gambit. Now Black has the choice between three moves:} ({Also playable is} 8. e3) 8... Ng4 (8... Qb6 9. e3 Bg4 (9... Bf5 $5) 10. Be2 Bxe2 11. Qxe2 e4 {In this line, Black often tries to exploit the weakened light squares with his knights. He is usually able to win back the pawn on d5, but this generally leaves him with an inferior position, as White will be able to activate his remaining pieces and the pawn on e4 becomes a weakness.}) (8... e4 {This is probably the weakest of Black's options.} 9. Bg2 Re8 10. O-O Bf5 {Now White has the pleasant choice between} 11. Be3 ({and} 11. Na3) 11... Bxe3 12. fxe3 Bg6 13. Qd4 Nbd7 14. Nd2 $16) 9. e3 f5 10. Be2 {Preparing 0-0 while at the same time preventing f5-f4.} Nd7 (10... Nf6 11. O-O f4 $5 12. exf4 exf4 13. Bxf4 Bh3 {, and now White must not be greedy:} 14. Nd2 $1 (14. Re1 $4 Bxf2+ 15. Kxf2 Qb6+ $19) 14... Bxf1 15. Bxf1 $16) ({The immediate} 10... Nxf2 $2 11. Kxf2 f4 12. Kg2 $18 {runs out of steam very quickly.}) 11. O-O (11. a3 $14) 11... Ndf6 12. Nd2 $14) 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. e4 d6 (6... Bg7 7. Be3 Ng4 {In this particular case, White can prevent the 7...Ng4-variation by playing 7.Be2. However, this is not always possible. For example, Black can choose the move-order 1.c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 g6 5.e4 Bg7 6.Be3 Nf6 7.Nc3 Ng4.} 8. Qxg4 Nxd4 9. Qd1 {Now Black has two moves that lead to very different positions:} Ne6 {, intending to set up a dark-square blockade on both sides of the board} ({, and} 9... e5 {, fortifying the knight on d4.})) 7. Be2 Bg7 (7... Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 (9. Bg5 {mostly leads to the same positions.}) 9... O-O 10. Qd2 Be6 11. Rc1 Qa5 12. b3 Rfc8 13. f3 a6 14. Na4 $1 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Nd7 16. g4 $14 {White will expand on the kingside and transfer his knight to d5 at a good moment.}) 8. Be3 O-O 9. O-O Bd7 10. h3 {This relatively new idea scores extremely well and creates very difficult problems for Black.} Nxd4 (10... a5 $2 11. Ndb5 $16) 11. Bxd4 Bc6 12. Qc2 {Now Black would like to stabilise his position with a7-a5, Nd7 and an eventual Nc5. However, he always falls one tempo short:} a5 (12... Nd7 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. b4 b6 15. Rad1 a5 16. b5 Bb7 17. Bg4 $1 Nc5 18. e5 $16) 13. Rad1 {Already threatening c4-c5.} Nd7 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Bg4 {Black cannot prevent the trade of his knight without allowing either c4-c5 or e4-e5.} Re8 16. Bxd7 Bxd7 17. a4 $1 $16 {White has a small but very stable and lasting advantage due to the fact that Black doesn't have any pawn breaks, and the scope of his bishop is limited by White's pawns.} *

