1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. a3 Bc5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. e4 O-O $1 9. Be2 b6 10. O-O $1 Bb7 11. Bf4 d6 12. Rc1 Rc8 13. Re1 Ne5 14. Nd2 Nfd7 {With this move, Black reorganises her pieces and gains the option of playing g7-g5 whenever f2-f4 is threatened. This would secure the e5-square for Black's knight, but also considerably weaken Black's kingside. So it should be regarded as a useful resource, but not as a move that she should play lightly.} ({Another way to play the position is} 14... a6 15. Bg3 Qc7 16. f4 Ned7 17. b4 Rfe8 18. Bd3 Qb8 19. Qe2 $14 {Black has a hard time realising any pawn breaks, as d6-d5 can always be met with cxd5 cxd5 e4-e5.}) 15. Be3 (15. Bg3 {was also possible. The bishop is useful on the h2-b8 diagonal, but on the other hand,} g5 $5 {may gain in strenght now, and the bishop would be better positioned on e3.}) 15... Qc7 (15... g5 {looks consistent but also slightly risky. Play might continue} 16. f3 Qc7 17. b4 Qb8 ({The attempt to gain the initiative with aggressive play immediately backfires:} 17... f5 $2 18. exf5 Rxf5 19. Nb5 Qb8 20. Nd4 $18) 18. Bf1 $14 {White is very solid on the kingside, and after some preparation, a breakthrough on the queenside will become possible. At the same time, the advanced g-pawn may become a liability.}) 16. b4 Qb8 17. f4 Ng6 18. g3 $14 {White is slowly expanding while keeping everything protected. At the same time, Black lacks an active plan.} Rfe8 19. Bf3 Qa8 20. Bf2 Ngf8 21. Qe2 Qb8 22. Red1 g6 $2 23. e5 $3 $16 {An amazing move by the world champion. Now the e5-pawn appears to be weak, but in fact Black has no way to put pressure on it and her f8-knight is extremely passive.} Bc6 (23... dxe5 24. fxe5 Bxf3 25. Nxf3 {also leaves Black in a cramped position - her minor pieces can barely move.}) 24. Bd4 Red8 25. Bxc6 Rxc6 26. Nf3 dxe5 27. fxe5 Rdc8 28. Ne4 Qc7 29. Nfd2 a6 30. Nf2 Bg5 31. Rf1 Bxd2 32. Qxd2 Nxe5 33. Bxe5 Qxe5 34. Ng4 Rd6 35. Nh6+ Kg7 36. Rxf7+ Kh8 37. Qf2 Qd4 38. c5 bxc5 39. Qxd4+ Rxd4 40. Rxc5 Rcd8 41. Rcc7 Rd1+ 42. Kg2 R1d2+ 43. Kh3 R2d5 44. Ng4 Rh5+ 45. Kg2 Rd2+ 46. Kf3 Rf5+ 47. Ke3 Rxf7 48. Rxf7 Rd8 49. Nf6 Rb8 50. Kf4 h6 51. Ke5 a5 52. bxa5 Ra8 53. a6 1-0

