1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. a3 Be7 7. e4 O-O 8. Nf3 $1 d6 9. Be2 b6 10. O-O Bb7 11. Bf4 $1 a6 12. Rc1 Rc8 13. b4 (13. Re1 $144) 13... Ng4 14. Nd2 Nge5 15. Be3 {Preventing Nd4 and creating the option of f2-f4.} Re8 ({As usual in such positions,} 15... f5 $2 {only serves the purpose of self-destruction:} 16. exf5 Rxf5 17. f4 Nd7 18. Bg4 Rf6 19. Nde4 $18) (15... g5 $6 {prevents f2-f4, but with} 16. Na4 $1 Nd7 17. Nf3 $1 $16 {, White discourages the knights from using that square by other means. Obviously, Black would now prefer his g-pawn back on g7.}) 16. Kh1 Bf8 17. f3 $1 {The exclamation mark is not only given for 17.f3's objective value. White is aware of the fact that Black hardly has any way to improve his position. So he decides to first stabilise his centre and wait for a good (or even better) moment to expand.} ({The straightforward} 17. f4 {was also good.}) 17... Nd7 {Black doesn't really have a good alternative to making waiting moves.} ({The complications after} 17... a5 18. Qb3 axb4 19. axb4 d5 20. cxd5 Nxb4 21. Bb5 exd5 22. Bxe8 {favour White.}) 18. Qe1 $6 {Not a good square for the queen. It is a standard idea in the Hedgehog to move the queen to f2 for maximum pressure against b6, but in this position it was important to keep Black's a6-a5 idea under control.} (18. Qb3 $142) (18. Re1 $142) 18... a5 $132 {Now White cannot keep the tension.} 19. b5 Ncb8 $2 ({Much better was} 19... Nce5 {, with dynamic equality after} 20. f4 Ng6 $132) 20. Na4 d5 21. cxd5 Rxc1 22. Qxc1 exd5 23. Bg1 Re6 ({No better was} 23... dxe4 24. Nxe4 Bxe4 25. fxe4 Rxe4 26. Bc4 Re7 27. Qf4 $16) 24. Bd1 dxe4 25. Nxe4 Ne5 26. Bb3 Rg6 27. Rd1 Nbd7 28. Nac3 Qh4 29. Bd5 Bxd5 30. Nxd5 Rh6 31. Rd4 Qh5 32. Nf4 Qh4 33. Nd5 Qh5 34. Qf4 Qg6 35. a4 Qe6 36. Qd2 Qf5 37. Ne3 Qf4 38. Rxd7 Nxd7 39. Qxd7 Re6 40. Qd1 Qc7 41. Nd5 Qb7 42. Qd4 f5 43. Qc4 Kh8 44. Nf4 Re8 45. Ng5 1-0

