1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 b6 $5 5. Nc3 Bb7 6. f3 d6 7. e4 e6 8. Be3 Be7 9. Be2 a6 10. O-O O-O 11. Qd2 Nbd7 12. Rac1 (12. a4 {is possible in this position, but Black can achieve reasonable counterplay with either} Rc8 ({or} 12... Re8 13. a5 d5 $132) 13. a5 Ne5 $132 {The point of this manoeuvre is that White cannot play} 14. b3 {due to} bxa5 {, and now the desirable Nb3xa5 is not possible anymore.}) 12... Qc7 13. Rfd1 Rac8 14. a3 {After developing all his pieces, White prepares his kingside expansion. a2-a3 may look unneccessary, but it is useful for two reasons: 1) When Black's queen leaves the c-file, a pawn on b4 would otherwise become a target after d6-d5. 2) It vacates the a2-square.} Qb8 (14... Ne5 {doesn't threaten anything, as the pawn is poisoned:} 15. b4 Qb8 16. Na4 ({or} 16. Qa2)) 15. b4 Rfe8 16. Kh1 {Defending against Black's following manoeuvre.} Bd8 17. Bg1 Bc7 18. Qa2 $1 {A strong multi-purpose move. From a2 White's queen supports a3-a4-a5 while at the same time discouraging d6-d5 ideas.} Nf8 $6 {Transferring the knight to the kingside. This is a standard manoeuvre in the Hedgehog, but looks too risky here, as White stands ready to start his queenside play and it withdraws a defender.} 19. Nb3 Ng6 20. a4 h5 21. a5 bxa5 22. Nxa5 $16 Ba8 $2 (22... Bxa5 $8) 23. b5 $18 axb5 24. Nxb5 h4 $4 25. Ba7 1-0

