1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 b6 5. Nc3 Bb7 6. f3 d6 7. e4 e6 8. Be3 Nbd7 9. Qb3 $1 ({The immediate} 9. g4 $1 {is also good, with the possible follow-up} h6 10. h4 Be7 11. Qd2 Rc8 12. O-O-O Ne5 13. Rg1 $3 {The attack on c4 can easily be ignored, as White is happy to trade his only undeveloped piece for Black's most active one.} Nxc4 14. Bxc4 Rxc4 15. g5 $16) 9... Be7 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O-O a6 12. g4 Rc8 13. Kb1 Re8 $6 14. Rhg1 $6 ({Much better is} 14. h4 $1 {, intending h4-h5 and g4-g5. The following sacrificial attempt by Black looks scary but fails:} Nc5 15. Qc2 b5 16. cxb5 Ncxe4 17. fxe4 Bxe4 18. Nxe4 ({Also good enough for a large advantage is the simple} 18. Bd3 $16) 18... Rxc2 19. Nxf6+ Bxf6 20. Nxc2 $18 {White has too much material for the queen.}) ({Also good is} 14. g5 $5 Nh5 15. Rhg1 g6 16. Qc2 $16 {Now after} Ne5 17. b3 {, f3-f4 is a very strong threat.}) 14... g6 15. a3 $2 {A serious loss of time in a sharp position. This and her next two moves show that the white player somehow lost the thread.} (15. h4 {was still good, for example} e5 16. Nc2 Nc5 17. Bxc5 Rxc5 18. Ne3 Rc8 (18... Bf8 19. Bf1 Nd7 (19... Rc8 20. g5 (20. Bh3 Rb8 21. Ncd5 (21. Rd2) (21. g5 Nh5 22. Ncd5)) 20... Nh5 21. Bh3 Rb8 22. Ned5 $16) 20. g5 $16) (18... Nd7 19. g5 $16 Nf8 20. Na4 Rc6 21. Nd5 Ne6 22. Naxb6 Nd4 23. Rxd4 $18) 19. h5 $16) 15... Bf8 16. Bf2 $2 (16. h4 d5 17. cxd5 exd5 18. h5 dxe4 19. hxg6 hxg6) 16... Qc7 17. Nc2 $2 Nc5 18. Qa2 Bg7 19. Ne3 Nfd7 20. Be1 Ne5 21. b4 Ncd7 22. Qd2 d5 23. exd5 exd5 24. Bg3 d4 25. Qxd4 Nxf3 26. Qd3 Nde5 27. Bxf3 Bxf3 28. Ned5 Qxc4 29. Qxc4 Nxc4 30. Rd3 Bxg4 31. Ka2 Be2 32. Rgd1 Bxd1 33. Rxd1 Ne3 34. Rd3 Nxd5 35. Nxd5 Re2+ 0-1

