1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nf3 cxd4 4. Nxd4 b6 5. Nc3 Bb7 6. f3 d6 7. e4 e6 8. Be3 Nbd7 9. Qb3 $1 {Preparing 0-0-0, followed by kingside play. The queen's placement on b3 is counter-intuitive, but fulfills the very important purpose of over-protecting c4.} ({The same plan doesn't work with} 9. Qd2 {due to} Rc8 10. O-O-O $2 Ne5 {, and White is forced to weaken his king's position.}) ({Equally good is the immediate} 9. g4 $1 {, intending to play Qb3 and 0-0-0 later.}) 9... a6 ({The seemingly logical and tempo-gaining response} 9... Nc5 $2 {in fact achieves less than nothing, as the knight only blocks Black's play on the c-file:} 10. Qc2 Be7 11. O-O-O O-O 12. Kb1 Rc8 13. g4 a6 14. g5 Ne8 (14... Nfd7 15. b4 {even loses the unfortunate knight.}) 15. h4 Qc7 16. Qg2 $16) 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Kb1 Qc7 ({Here and in many other positions of this line,} 11... Ne5 {can be easily parried with} 12. Na4) (11... Be7 12. g4 O-O 13. g5 Ne8 14. h4 Ne5 (14... Nc5 15. Qc2) 15. Rc1 Qc7 16. Na4 Nxf3 17. Nxf3 Bxe4+ 18. Ka1 Bxf3 19. Bxb6 Qb7) 12. Be2 h5 $5 {An interesting idea in many Sicilian-type positions in which White intends to play g2-g4. Black considerably slows down White's play on the kingside. This has a downside, though: Black now lacks a safe place for his king. And if White finally achieves his pawn advance, it becomes much stronger, as Black has weakened his kingside.} 13. g3 {The immediate 13.h3? can be answered with 13...h4, and White's g-pawn is fixed. So White slowly prepares h2-h3, to make a later g3-g4 possible.} Ne5 14. Rc1 Be7 15. h3 Nfd7 16. Ka1 $6 ({Better was the immediate} 16. g4 $1 $40 {, with good attacking chances.}) 16... h4 17. g4 g5 18. Rhd1 Ng6 19. Qc2 Rg8 20. Qd2 Nf4 21. Bf1 Qd8 22. Qf2 Bf6 23. Nde2 Nxe2 24. Bxe2 Be5 25. Na4 Nc5 26. Nxc5 bxc5 27. Bd2 Bd4 28. Be3 e5 29. Rd3 Qf6 30. Rb3 Bc6 31. Bd1 Kd7 32. Qd2 Qd8 33. Ra3 Qb6 34. Rb3 Qd8 35. Ra3 Qb6 36. Rb3 Qd8 1/2-1/2

