1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 b6 5. Nc3 Bb7 6. f3 a6 7. e4 Qc7 8. Be3 e6 9. Be2 d6 10. O-O Nbd7 $6 {Generally the correct square for the knight in hedgehog setups, but in combination with an early Qc7, this is slightly premature, as the game will show.} ({Black should have first finished his kingside development with} 10... Be7 11. Qd2 O-O {, and now} 12. a4 $6 {would be harmless due to} Nc6 $1 {, preventing a4-a5.}) 11. a4 $1 {Black cannot take control of the a5-square or exchange the d4-knight anymore, which will soon devastate her position. And with her kingside development lagging, she is not in time for quick counterplay with Re8 and d6-d5.} Be7 12. a5 O-O ({After} 12... bxa5 13. Nb3 O-O 14. Nxa5 $16 {, White will next play Qd2, Rfc1 and b2-b4, with a huge advantage. Black lacks space, counterplay, and a6 is permanently weak. But no matter who releases the tension, the structure on the queenside will be the same.}) 13. Qd2 Bd8 14. axb6 Nxb6 15. Rfc1 $16 Qb8 ({This pawn is poisoned, as usual:} 15... Nxc4 16. Bxc4 Qxc4 17. Na4 {, and Black's queen has no squares.}) 16. b4 Nbd7 17. Rab1 Ne5 18. c5 d5 19. f4 Neg4 20. e5 Nxe3 21. Qxe3 Ne8 22. b5 axb5 23. Ncxb5 Qc8 24. Nd6 Nxd6 25. cxd6 Qb8 26. Nc6 1-0

