1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d5 6. cxd5 Bc5 7. N5c3 O-O 8. g3 Qb6 9. e3 Bg4 10. Be2 Bxe2 (10... Bh3 {looks promising, but after} 11. g4 {, White already has a large advantage. The main threat is Rg1-g3, winning the bishop. After} h5 {, White has two ways to obtain a near-winning position:} 12. g5 (12. gxh5 Nbd7 13. Rg1 $16) 12... Ne8 13. Nd2 $16) 11. Qxe2 e4 {This is necessary now, as White was threatening to play e3-e4, fortifying his pawn on d5.} 12. a3 {Preventing any Bb4-ideas and preparing an eventual b2-b4.} ({White can also start with} 12. O-O Nbd7 13. Nd2 Rfe8 {, after which again, Bb4 becomes a threat and} 14. a3 {the best move.} (14. Na4 $2 {is a big positional mistake, as it is Black who should be willing to invest time in such a swap of bishop and knight. Black's main idea is to penetrate the white position on the light squares, and after this trade he has one extra minor piece on these, and the annoying pressure against e4 is gone.} Qd6 15. Nxc5 Nxc5 $17) 14... a5 15. b3 Qd6 16. Bb2 Nb6 17. Nc4 (17. Kg2 Nbxd5 18. Nxd5 Nxd5 19. Rfd1 Qe6 20. Rac1 Ba7 21. Nc4 Rad8 22. Bd4 Bxd4 23. Rxd4 Nf6) 17... Nxc4 18. bxc4) ({The immediate} 12. Nd2 $6 {would be desirable, but Black has the unpleasant response} Bb4 $1 13. O-O Bxc3 14. bxc3 Nxd5 15. Nxe4 Re8 16. Qf3 Nd7 17. c4 N5f6 18. Nxf6+ Nxf6 19. Ba3 Qc7 20. Qd1 Qxc4 $11) 12... Nbd7 13. Nd2 Rfe8 14. b4 Bf8 15. O-O Qc7 16. Bb2 Nb6 {As often in this line, Black can win back the pawn on d5, but this does not provide him with equality.} 17. Nb5 ({Also good was the simple} 17. Rac1 Qd7 18. Rfd1 Nbxd5 19. Nxd5 Nxd5 (19... Qxd5 20. Bxf6 $16) 20. Nb3 $16 {All of White's pieces are more active than all of Black's, and the e4-pawn is weak.}) 17... Qd7 18. d6 ({Even stronger was} 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. d6 Rac8 ({or} 19... Bxd6 20. Nxd6 Qxd6 21. Qg4+ $18) 20. Nc7 Red8 21. Nxe4 $18) 18... Nfd5 19. Rac1 Bxd6 20. Nxd6 Qxd6 21. Rfd1 Qe6 22. Nb3 $3 {Now Black can seemingly reduce the pressure by tactical means, but White has calculated further:} Nf4 23. gxf4 Qxb3 {The annoying knight has left the board, but now the g-file is opened for White's rooks.} 24. Kh1 Qe6 (24... Na4 25. Bd4 Qxa3 26. Ra1 Qb3 {loses to} 27. Rdb1 Nc3 28. Qg4 $18) 25. Rg1 f6 26. Qh5 Nd5 27. Rg3 {Black cannot defend against the onslaught of all of White's remaining pieces.} Kh8 28. Rcg1 Re7 29. Rh3 Qg8 (29... h6 30. Rg6 $18) 30. Qf5 Rf8 31. Bd4 $3 b6 32. Rg4 Rc7 33. Rh5 $3 Ne7 34. Qxe4 Rf7 (34... f5 {doesn't help:} 35. Rxg7) 35. Rg1 g6 36. Re5 Nc6 37. Re8 1-0

