1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 g6 3. e4 Bg7 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Nc3 Ng4 8. Qxg4 Nxd4 9. Qd1 Ne6 (9... Nc6 {This is possible but does not solve any problem. The knight may look more natural here but also fails to control the important squares f4 and g5.} 10. Qd2 {It is important to prevent Bxc3, after which Black has good play against White's damaged structure.} O-O (10... Qa5 11. Rc1) 11. Rc1 d6 12. Be2 {White has more space and no weaknesses. He intends to simply finish development and play Nd5 at some point, with a large advantage. If Black makes use of the only pawn break at his disposal, this only quickens his demise:} f5 $6 13. exf5 Bxf5 14. O-O Rc8 15. b3 Kh8 16. f4 $16) 10. Rc1 b6 (10... Qa5 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O d6 (12... b6 13. Qd5 $16)) 11. Be2 Bb7 12. f3 Rc8 13. O-O $16 h5 14. Rf2 h4 15. Bf1 Qc7 16. Nd5 Qb8 17. f4 Bc6 18. b4 g5 19. fxg5 Be5 20. h3 Bh2+ 21. Kh1 Bg3 22. Rf3 Rg8 23. Qd2 Qe5 24. Rf5 Qg7 25. Be2 Qg6 26. Bg4 Ng7 27. b5 Nxf5 28. Bxf5 Qd6 29. c5 bxc5 30. bxc6 Rxc6 31. Rd1 Kf8 32. Qe2 Qe5 33. Bxd7 Rd6 34. Bb5 Qxe4 35. Bxc5 Rxd5 36. Rxd5 Qxd5 37. Qxe7+ Kg7 38. Qf6+ Kh7 39. Qh6# 1-0

