1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 {g6 is a move that is played by King's Indian and Grunfeld players. With the Reti, we avoid those openings and drag our opponents into our territory. These positions are more based on ideas and there is little theory. We will study different set-ups from Black such as d6-c5, b6-c5, and c5-d6-e5.} (2... b6 {We need to be aware of b6 move orders - sometimes there can be an idea after Bb7 to take our f3 knight and damage our pawn structure, so on b6 we can reply with g3!, in order to meet Bb7 with Bg2, defending the knight on f3} 3. g3 (3. b3 Bb7 4. Bb2 c5 5. g3 Bxf3 6. exf3 {This may be a bit annoying, so keep the aforementioned idea in mind - when the opponent is ready to fianchetto their bishop, we should get ready to fianchetto ours!}) 3... Bb7 4. Bg2 g6 5. b3 Bg7 6. Bb2 O-O 7. O-O c5 {Symmetrical position in which White can play} 8. d4 $1 {Soon you will see a very interesting idea played by Aronian} (8. Nc3 $5 {is also possible})) 3. b3 {There are many move orders so that's why we will study set-ups} Bg7 4. Bb2 {Black can play moves such as 0-0, d6, or c5.} O-O 5. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gh1a8] e3 is also possible but in general, our light-squared bishop has been proven to be better on the h1-a8 diagonal} *

