1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. b3 Bg7 4. Bb2 O-O 5. g3 c5 6. Bg2 Nc6 (6... d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Bxg7 Kxg7 {As a general rule when the pawn is on b3 and we want to play d4 - we should be careful of Qa5+ or first taking cxd4 and then Qa5+} 9. O-O {So we simply castle first and now we want to play d4!} (9. d4 Qa5+ $11 (9... cxd4 10. Qxd4+ {Taking with the queen is possible but Black will gain a tempo later with Nc6})) 9... Nc6 10. d4 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Kg8 12. Nxc6 bxc6 {[%csl Gb1,Rc6] The pawn on c6 is a permanent weakness. Now we need to develop the knight, on Nd2, Nc3 might be annoying, so that's why Qc1} 13. Qc1 Qb6 14. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gc3a4]} Nxc3 15. Qxc3 $16 {[%csl Rc6]}) 7. O-O d5 {[%cal Gd5d4] This is a typical mistake from Black. Black's idea is to play d4 but it's White to move and now we will take the pawn} (7... d6 8. d4 {This is objectively the best move for White} cxd4 (8... Ne4 9. Nbd2 Nxd2 10. Qxd2 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bxd4 12. Bxd4 Nxd4 13. Qxd4 $14) 9. Nxd4 Bd7 10. Nc3 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Ng4 12. Qd2 $14) 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Bxg7 $1 (9. Qc1 {This is a typical move but taking on g7 is better, after Kxg7, the king is exposed. Additionally, Black has Nd4! in this position}) 9... Kxg7 10. d4 $1 (10. d3 $6 {Is too slow, after e5 Black will manage to stabilize the position and will have a good game} e5 11. Nbd2 b6 12. Rc1 Bb7 $15 13. Qc2 f6 14. Qb2 Qd7 {Black has a comfortable position}) 10... cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. Qxd4+ Nf6 {Do we want to keep the queens on the board? At the moment, yes, because our queen is more active. Later on, we can exchange the queens under more favorable circumstances} 13. Qe5 $1 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gf1d1,Ga1c1] White has a risk-free advantage} (13. Qb2 $5 Kg8 14. Nc3 Qa5 15. Rfd1 $14 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gb3b4]}) 13... Be6 (13... Qd6 14. Qxd6 exd6 15. Rd1 Rd8 16. Nc3 $16 Rb8 {Rb8 in order to protect the pawn on b7, so the Bc8 can develop. Now White has several moves to choose from, such as Nb5, Rd4, Rac1 and so on} 17. Rd4 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Ga1d1,Gd1d6]}) (13... Kg8 14. Nc3 Re8 15. Rfd1 Qb6 {[%cal Gb6f2,Gf6g4,Gg4f2,Gg4e5] Be aware of this idea. The threat is Qxf2 and then Ng4+} 16. Qd4 (16. Rac1 Qxf2+ {Here White has compensation but there is no need to allow this at all}) 16... Qxd4 17. Rxd4 $16 Rb8 18. Rc1 {The following is an example (not the best moves, the point is to reach the rook endgame on move 25) that even if a lot of pieces are traded, White can still have an advantage} Be6 19. Nd5 Nxd5 20. Bxd5 Bxd5 21. Rxd5 Rec8 22. Rxc8+ Rxc8 23. Rd7 Rb8 24. e3 e6 {As a Reti player, we always welcome endgames especially when we have an advantage or something to play on. For Black to activate the rook, he would need to sacrifice a pawn} 25. Kg2 a6 26. a4 b5 27. Rd6 bxa4 28. bxa4 Ra8 (28... a5 29. Ra6 $16) 29. a5 $16 {[%cal Gg3g4]}) 14. Bxb7 $1 Qb8 15. Qxb8 Raxb8 16. Ba6 Nd5 17. Bc4 Rfd8 18. Rc1 Rb6 19. Bxd5 $3 Rxd5 20. Nc3 Rd2 21. Rd1 Rc2 (21... Rbd6 22. Rxd2 Rxd2 23. Rc1 Bh3 24. f3 f6 25. Kf2 Be6 26. Ke1 Rb2 27. Kd1 g5 28. Rc2 Rxc2 29. Kxc2 $18) 22. Rac1 Rb2 23. Kf1 Rd6 24. Ke1 Bf5 25. Rxd6 exd6 26. Ra1 h5 27. Nd1 Rc2 28. Ne3 Rb2 29. Nd1 Rc2 30. Ne3 Rb2 31. Nc4 Rc2 32. Kd1 d5 33. Ne3 Rc6 34. Rc1 Ra6 35. Nxf5+ gxf5 36. a4 Rb6 37. Kc2 f4 38. Rd1 fxg3 39. hxg3 Rc6+ 40. Kb2 Rf6 41. f4 Re6 42. Rxd5 Rxe2+ 43. Kc3 Re3+ 44. Kc4 Rxg3 45. Rxh5 Rf3 46. Ra5 Rxf4+ 47. Kc3 Rf3+ 48. Kb4 Rf4+ 49. Ka3 Kf6 50. Rxa7 Ke6 51. a5 Kd6 52. b4 Kc6 53. Ka4 Rf5 54. Re7 Rf1 55. b5+ Kd6 56. Rb7 f5 57. b6 f4 58. Kb5 f3 59. Rf7 1-0

