1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. b3 Bg7 4. Bb2 O-O 5. g3 c5 6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O b6 {The combination of b6 and Nc6 is a bit strange as it blocks the bishop on b7} (7... d6 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 a6 11. Nc3 Nh5 12. Qd2 $16) (7... d5 {This leads to a risk-free advantage for White} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Bxg7 Kxg7 10. d4 $1) 8. d4 cxd4 (8... Bb7 9. d5 Na5 10. Nbd2 e6 11. e4 {When playing e4, be careful of Nxe4 tactics! Here Nxe4 is not working.} exd5 12. exd5 $16 {[%csl Ra5,Rb7] Our advantage is the closed bishop on b7, but more importantly - the misplaced knight on a5. It will take a really long time for that knight to somehow contribute to the battle}) 9. Nxd4 Bb7 10. Nc3 Rb8 {Black wants to trade pieces, Nxd4 and Bxg2 is the idea} 11. Nd5 (11. Nc2 $1 {We don't allow any trades} d6 (11... Na5 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. Bxg7 Ne3 14. Nxe3 Kxg7 15. Bh3 d6 16. Qd2 $16) 12. Qd2 Nd7 13. Rab1 {[%csl Gb2][%cal Gb1b2]} (13. Ne3 {Is also possible}) 13... a6 14. Rfd1 Re8 (14... Nc5 15. b4 $16) 15. Ne3 Bh6 (15... Ba8 16. Ncd5 $16) 16. f4 $16) 11... Nxd5 12. Bxd5 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Bxd5 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Qd4+ Kg8 16. cxd5 Rc8 {Too many pieces have been traded, although White still has a slightly better position} 17. Rac1 {It's not easy for Black to handle the position, one move such as d6 can give White a big advantage} Rc7 (17... d6 $6 18. Rc6 $16 Rxc6 19. dxc6 Qc7 20. Rc1 $16 {We can play on all sides of the board}) 18. Qe3 (18. d6 $14 {This should lead to a better position for White, isolating Black's d pawn}) 18... Re8 19. h4 h5 20. Rfd1 d6 21. Qf4 {White should have used the newly created weakness on c4 and should have played Rc6!} (21. Rc6 $1 $16) 21... e6 22. Rxc7 Qxc7 23. Rc1 Qd7 24. dxe6 Qxe6 25. e3 $14 {White has a small but long-lasting advantage - it's a game on 2 results, White will either win or draw} Qd7 26. Qf6 Re6 27. Qc3 Re7 28. Kg2 Qe6 29. Qc8+ Kg7 30. Qxe6 fxe6 31. Kf3 Rf7+ 32. Ke2 Kf6 33. e4 Rd7 34. a4 d5 35. exd5 Rxd5 36. Rc7 a5 37. Rb7 Rd6 38. Ke3 e5 39. f3 Ke6 40. g4 Rc6 41. Ke4 Rd6 42. Ke3 Rc6 1/2-1/2

