1. Nf3 b6 2. g3 (2. e4 {White should take the chance to transpose to a good 1. e4 opening} Bb7 3. Nc3 e6 4. d4 (4. a3 {To prevent Bb4 is also possible}) 4... Bb4 5. Bd3 Nf6 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf6e4,Gb7e4,Gb4e1]} 6. Nd2 $1 {[%cal Ga2a3] With a3 next}) 2... Bb7 3. Bg2 c5 4. O-O Nf6 5. c4 g6 6. b3 Bg7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Nc3 d5 9. Nxd5 Nxd5 10. Bxg7 Kxg7 11. cxd5 Qxd5 12. d4 cxd4 13. Qxd4+ Qxd4 14. Nxd4 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Nd7 16. Rfd1 Nf6 17. Nb5 Rfc8 18. Rac1 Rxc1 19. Rxc1 a6 20. Nd4 Rd8 21. e3 Nd5 22. Rc6 Rd6 23. Rxd6 exd6 {White has a small advantage which he managed to convert into a win later on} 24. Kf1 Kf8 25. Ke1 f5 26. Kd2 Ke8 27. Nc2 Kd7 28. Kd3 Nc7 29. e4 fxe4+ 30. Kxe4 $16 {White is now better because there is a potential for a distant passed pawn on the kingside} Ke6 31. Nd4+ Kf6 32. f4 d5+ 33. Ke3 Ke7 34. Nf3 Ne6 35. g4 Kd6 36. f5 gxf5 37. gxf5 Nd8 38. Kf4 Nf7 39. h4 h6 40. b4 a5 41. a3 axb4 42. axb4 Ke7 43. Ne5 Nd6 44. Ng4 Nf7 45. h5 Kd6 46. Ke3 Ng5 47. b5 Ne4 48. Kf4 Ke7 49. Ke5 Ng3 50. f6+ Kd7 51. Ne3 d4 52. Nd5 d3 1-0

