1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 {Here we need to play either d4 or b3} (2... g6 3. b3 {is our move order} Bg7 4. Bb2 O-O (4... d6 5. g3 O-O (5... e5 {Will transpose to d6-e5 set-ups}) 6. Bg2 c5 {d4 is possible, 0-0 is also good} 7. O-O Nc6 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 {[%cal Gc6d4,Gd1d4]} Bd7 10. Nc3 $14) (4... c5 5. g3) 5. g3 c5 6. Bg2 d6 {Will transpose from the variation 1.Nf3 Nf6, 2.c4 c5, 3.b3 g6}) 3. b3 b6 $5 (3... g6 4. Bb2 Bg7 5. g3 d6 6. Bg2 {There are various move orders so it's important to remember - when can White play d4? Only after Bg2!} (6. d4 {Not yet as we don't have Bg2. Black may have some Ne4 and Qa5+. We would like to meet Ne4 with 0-0 and then White would have a comfortable position with no problems}) 6... O-O {Black played c5 and d6. White can play d4 which is objectively the best move, or White can castle and after e5 d3, it will transpose to variations which we will study later. The plans for White are to play d4 whether now or at some point and reach a typical hedgehog position, or to allow the c5-d6-e5 structure and play a slow maneuvering game} 7. O-O (7. d4 Nc6 (7... Qa5+ 8. Bc3 $14) (7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 {Qxd4 Aronian's plan of Qc3, Rd1, Qe1 and Nc3 was when Black had b6 and Bb7. This is a different position} Nbd7 9. O-O Nc5 10. Nc3 Bd7 11. Qd2 {[%cal Gf1d1,Ga1c1]}) 8. O-O {This is the initial position of the setup with c5 d6. There are many move orders and for example, Black could have taken cxd4 on the previous move} (8. d5 {is also good})) 7... Nc6 8. d4 cxd4 (8... Ne4 9. Nbd2 (9. e3 $5 {[%cal Gd1e2,Ge2b2] Is also interesting. The idea is to play Qe2 and protect the bishop, with a potential d5 later on} Bg4 10. Qc1 $14) 9... Nxd2 10. Qxd2 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Bxd4 13. Qxd4 $14 Qc7 14. Rac1 {[%cal Gc4c5] The idea is to play c5 and reach an endgame with a risk-free advantage} Bf5 (14... Qc5 {We can avoid the trade but exchanging the queens leads to a comfortable position where White can press for a long time} 15. Qxc5 dxc5 16. Rfd1 {White takes control of the only open file} Rb8 17. Rd5 b6 18. Rcd1 Be6 (18... Bb7 $2 19. Rd7 $18) 19. R5d2 $14 {With later on improving the position slowly. Ideas such as Bd5 or pushing the pawns with f4, e4 can be good for White}) 15. c5 dxc5 16. Qxc5 (16. Rxc5 $5) 16... Qxc5 17. Rxc5 Rac8 18. Ra5 $14 {[%csl Ra7,Rb7]}) 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 {With a good position for White} Ne8 11. Qd2 Bxb2 12. Qxb2 Nf6 13. Nc3 $16) 4. g3 $1 {In order to meet Bb7 with Bg2, to protect the knight on f3} Bb7 5. Bg2 g6 6. Bb2 Bg7 7. O-O O-O {And now there are 2 ways to go: d4 or Nc3} 8. d4 $1 (8. Nc3 $1 d5 (8... d6 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 Nbd7 12. e4 Rc8 13. Qe2 $14 (13. f3 {is also possible})) 9. Nxd5 $1 Nxd5 10. Bxg7 Kxg7 11. cxd5 Qxd5 (11... Bxd5 $6 12. d4 $1 $16 (12. d3 $6 {Would again be too slow} Nc6 13. a3 e5 14. Qc2 a5 15. Qb2 f6 $15)) 12. d4 $1 cxd4 13. Qxd4+ Qxd4 14. Nxd4 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 $14 {See the games in the list for how to play this position}) 8... cxd4 9. Qxd4 Nc6 (9... d6 10. Nc3 Nbd7 11. Qd2 $1 Rc8 12. Rac1 (12. Ne1 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 $1 Nc5 14. f3 Qd7 15. e4 Qb7 16. Nd3 $14)) 10. Qc3 $1 {The amazing plan by Aronian! The idea is Rd1-Qe1-Nc3} Rc8 (10... Ne8 11. Qd2 Bxb2 12. Qxb2 Nf6 13. Nc3 d6 14. Rfd1 $14) 11. Rd1 Qc7 12. Qe1 $1 Qb8 13. Nc3 $14 Rfd8 14. Rac1 e6 15. e4 d6 16. Qe2 $14 *

