{[%evp 0,13,14,20,20,6,38,-1,-1,6,-2,-15,-4,-3,-3,-5]} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 (2... c5 {Here objectively best is d4, but b3 can be tried to transpose to the lines which will be seen now after ...g6} 3. d4) 3. b3 {Here I suggest the repertoire with b3 that takes us in pure Reti positions. This way we also avoid the King's Indian and Grunfeld} Bg7 4. Bb2 O-O 5. g3 {This is better than e3. Our light-squared bishop is better placed on g2 on the long diagonal.} d6 {Black aims to get a King's Indian type of set-up with d6 and e5} 6. Bg2 e5 7. d3 {This is the starting position of the set-up with d6-e5. After d3, there are 3 basic set-ups for Black: 1) Black can play normal moves such as Nc6, Re8, h6 and so on; 2) Black can play d6-e5 and c5, which is a combination of the two systems with c5 and e5; 3) There is a set-up with c6 and Nbd7. Black can also choose to go in some non-theoretical direction. We will study all the set-ups one by one.} (7. d4 $2 {Is not good since Black can play e4 and even sacrifice the pawn} e4 8. Nfd2 e3 $15) *

