{[%evp 0,33,14,20,20,-5,38,-1,-4,-4,7,-18,-3,-5,0,-7,-7,0,2,2,14,5,23,15,31,30,63,29,146,140,143,152,244,230,230,175]} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 {This is the move which players who aim to get the King's Indian will play} 3. b3 Bg7 4. Bb2 O-O 5. g3 (5. e3 {Is playable if you generally want to get out of book, but g3 is the main recommendation} d6 6. d4 e5 7. dxe5 Ng4 8. Nc3 $1 Nxe5 9. Be2 Nbd7 10. O-O Re8 11. Qd2 Nxf3+ 12. Bxf3 Ne5 13. Be2 $14) 5... d6 6. Bg2 e5 (6... Nbd7 {Here we have 2 choices, we can play d4 since we already played Bg2, and then we can castle and play a normal position, or we can ignore the idea of e5 and just castle. After e5 d3, we will be in the 3rd set-up for Black - d6-e5, Nbd7 and possibly c6}) 7. d3 Nc6 8. O-O {Here we don't need to learn theory but instead, we need to learn the plans for White. Here are some very educational sample lines to understand the plans. For starters, our next move is likely to be Nc3, simply developing the Knight.} Nh5 (8... Re8 9. Nc3 {White is intending to play Nd2, a3, b4, Nd5 perhaps, standard moves for these types of positions.} h6 {Black wants to develop with Be6, so h6 is preventing the move Ng5 which would attack the bishop. Now a3 is good, and Nd2 is also good.} (9... Be6 $5 10. Ng5 {We want to take the Be6} Bd7 (10... h6 $2 {Is a mistake because it allows the trade of the Be6} 11. Nxe6 fxe6 12. a3 d5 13. b4 $16 {The central pawn structure which Black has is very difficult to use}) 11. a3 a5 12. Rb1 Rb8 13. e3 h6 14. Nge4 Nxe4 (14... Nh7 15. Ba1 f5 16. Nd2 $14) 15. dxe4 $1 {is the best move for White - opening the d file and taking firm control over the d5 square} (15. Nxe4 {is also playable} f5 16. Nc3 g5 17. Nd5 Be6 (17... f4 18. b4 axb4 19. axb4 fxe3 20. fxe3 $16) (17... g4 18. d4 (18. b4 h5 19. f3 $1 $16) 18... e4 19. Nf4 $16) 18. b4 (18. f4 {is a typical idea in these structures}) 18... axb4 19. axb4 $14 g4 20. b5 Ne7 21. e4 $16)) (9... e4 10. Nxe4 {Almost always White captures with the knight} Nxe4 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 (11... Nxf2 12. Rxf2 Kxg7 13. Qd2 $16) 12. dxe4 Rxe4 13. Nd2 $3 {The knight is going for the c3 square and from there the knight can jump on d5} Re8 14. Ne4 Bf5 15. Nc3 Qd7 16. Qd2 Bh3 17. Bxh3 Qxh3 18. f4 $16 {[%csl Re5,Gf4][%cal Gc3d5,Gd2c3,Gd2b2,Gb2g7,Rc6e5,Re5g4] Taking the e5 square under control}) 10. a3 (10. Nd2 {I would like to show the idea after} Be6 {that Nd5 may not always be great for White. The difference with a2-a3 and a7-a5 included is that Black would not have Bxd5 cxd5 and Nb4, because if the knight goes to e7 it will be badly placed, but without a3-a5 included, Black would be able to keep the knight active with Nb4!} 11. Nd5 Bxd5 12. cxd5 Nb4 {The engine suggests this position is still good for White after e4! as White would have compensation for the pawn, but it's not necessary to come to this position with White}) 10... Be6 (10... a5 11. Nd2 $1 {Another typical move from White. Generally, we don't jump Nd5 with the knight still on f3} Be6 {Black may be preparing d5, although it's not really a big threat since we also have an advantage there, we can prevent it with Nd5} 12. Nd5 Bxd5 (12... Nh7 13. e3 f5 14. b4 axb4 15. axb4 Rb8 16. b5 Ne7 17. Ra7 $16 (17. f4 $5) 17... Nxd5 18. cxd5 Bd7 19. Qb3 b6 (19... g5 20. b6 cxb6 21. Nc4 $18) 20. Rc1 Rc8 21. Qc4 g5 22. Ba1 f4 23. Ne4 g4 $2 24. exf4 exf4 25. Bxg7 Kxg7 26. gxf4 $18) 13. cxd5 Ne7 {The knight usually wants to go to b4 instead since on e7 is a bit misplaced, but this was not possible with the inclusion of the moves a3 and a5} 14. e4 $16) 11. b4 d5 12. b5 Na5 13. Nxe5 $16) (8... Bd7 9. Nc3 a6 {The plans for White can be Nd2 (or sometimes Ng5, for example if there is a bishop on e6) , we will play e3 sooner or later, a3-b4, and Nd5.} (9... e4 $6 {Is not working. We always capture with the knight, for example:} 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxg7 Nxf2 12. Rxf2 Kxg7 13. Qd2 $14) 10. Nd2 Re8 {White can play many moves - e3, a3, Nd5. Which one to play can be usually decided by calculation} 11. a3 Qc8 {Here White can also ignore the threat Bh3 by playing moves such as Nd5, b4, e3, or he can react with Re1, aiming to meet Bh3 with Bh1, although generally there is no problem in the Reti to exchange the light-squared Bishops.} 12. e3 (12. Re1 Bh3 13. Bh1) 12... Bh3 13. b4 $14) (8... Ne8 9. Nc3 f5 10. Nd2 f4 {Black wants to play the annoying move Bg4 (this idea is also seen in the Nh5 variation instead of Ne8), and again, White should react with e3!} (10... h5 11. Nd5 h4 12. e3 hxg3 13. hxg3 {Recapturing with the h pawn is good and safe for White. It's tough for Black to find a proper way to proceed with the attack} (13. fxg3 {is also possible}) 13... g5 14. b4 f4 {This creates too many weaknesses on the light squares} 15. Ne4 fxe3 16. fxe3 $18 {The attack didn't accomplish anything for Black}) 11. e3 $1 {Preventing Bg4} (11. Nd5 Bg4)) 9. Nc3 {We block the diagonal and with that, e4 from Black is prevented} (9. a3 $2 {We need to be careful when the bishops are on the same diagonal, there can be tactics. We need to be more careful than Black since our Bb2 is not protected} e4 10. Bxg7 exf3 11. Bxf8 fxg2 12. Kxg2 Qxf8 $19) 9... f5 {On all these lines I will play the following moves for sure: Nd2, Nd5 (be careful to avoid blunders such as ...e4 from Black), e3, a3-b4, and maybe also Rb1. Be careful every time with the move orders!} 10. Nd2 $1 {This is the best move in my opinion. The reason why White has a very good score in such positions and Black loses all the time, is that Black is trying to attack a very well-defended king. With h2-g3-f2 and e3 to be played soon, we are prepared for Black's attack, while our moves are slowly improving the position - Nd5, e3, a3, b4 and so on. Additionally, by rushing in the attack, Black can create weaknesses that can also be exploited.} (10. e3 $5 {This was played in the game} f4 (10... e4 $2 11. dxe4 fxe4 12. Nd2 $18) 11. exf4 (11. Nd2 $1 $14 Be6 12. Nd5) 11... exf4 12. Qd2 Bg4 13. Rae1 $3 $14 Qd7 14. Nd5 fxg3 15. fxg3 Rae8 16. Rxe8 Rxe8 17. b4 Nd8 18. Bxg7 Qxg7 19. Re1 Rxe1+ 20. Qxe1 Nf6 21. Nd4 c6 22. Ne3 Bd7 23. Nb3 Qe7 24. Qf2 b6 25. a4 Nf7 26. b5 c5 27. Nd2 Kg7 28. Ne4 Nxe4 29. Bxe4 Qe5 30. h4 Qa1+ 31. Kg2 Qxa4 32. Bd5 Ne5 33. g4 h6 34. g5 hxg5 35. hxg5 Bf5 36. Qh4 Kf8 37. Qh8+ Ke7 38. Nxf5+ gxf5 39. Qf6+ Kd7 40. Qxf5+ Kc7 41. Qh7+ Kd8 42. Qg8+ Kc7 43. Qg7+ Nd7 44. Be4 Qd1 45. Qe7 Qg4+ 46. Kf2 Qf4+ 47. Ke2 Qh2+ 48. Kf3 Qe5 49. Qxe5 Nxe5+ 50. Kf4 Kd7 51. Kf5 Ke7 52. g6 Nd7 53. Bd5 Kf8 54. Ke6 Ne5 55. Be4 Ng4 56. Kxd6 Nf2 57. Kc7 Nd1 58. Kb7 Nb2 59. Kxa7 Na4 60. Bf3 {Marin, Mihail - Berg, Emanuel, 1-0, 2015}) (10. Nd5 $4 e4 11. Bxg7 exf3 12. Bxf8 fxg2 $17) 10... f4 (10... Bd7 11. Nd5 {Moves like e3 or a3 were also playable} f4 12. e3 $1 $14 {Not allowing Bg4!} Rb8 (12... fxe3 13. fxe3 Rxf1+ 14. Qxf1 Rb8 15. Ne4 $16) 13. Ne4 $14) (10... Kh8 11. Nd5 Bd7 (11... f4 12. e3) 12. e3 Rb8 13. b4 $1 (13. f4 $1 exf4 14. Bxg7+ Nxg7 15. exf4 $14 (15. gxf4 $14)) 13... f4 (13... Ne7 14. a4 Nxd5 (14... c6 15. Nxe7 Qxe7 16. b5 c5 17. Nb1 f4 18. Nc3 fxe3 19. fxe3 Rxf1+ 20. Qxf1 Qg5 21. Qe2 Bh6 22. Ne4 $1 $18 (22. Re1 $16)) 15. cxd5 c6 16. Qb3 f4 17. exf4 exf4 18. Bxg7+ Nxg7 19. dxc6 bxc6 20. Qc3) 14. Ne4) 11. e3 $1 $16 {[%cal Gd2e4,Gc3d5] Whenever f4 is played, White needs to be careful of the move Bg4 which can be annoying. Even though now h3 is not possible because it loses a pawn, White doesn't want to play h3 in general, as it would weaken the kingside, that's why e3!} (11. Nd5 $6 Bg4 $3 $132 12. Ne4 $2 Nd4 $1 13. Bxd4 exd4 $15) 11... fxe3 (11... Qe8 12. Nd5 Qf7 13. b4 $16 {Whenever White can play b4 in one move (a3 not being required), White should do it without a3, since the a pawn can go to a4 directly which means saving a tempo} (13. Ne4 $2 {We need to be careful of the f3 push} f3) 13... Nd8 (13... Be6 14. b5 Nd8 15. exf4 exf4 16. Bxg7 Qxg7 17. Re1 $14) 14. b5 c6 15. Nc3 Be6 16. Nce4 $16) 12. fxe3 Bh6 13. Qe2 $16 {Nd5 was also possible, but Qe2 protects the pawn and also connects the rooks, so it's a better move in this position} Qg5 14. Rxf8+ $1 Kxf8 15. Nd5 $18 Qd8 16. Rf1+ Kg8 17. Ne4 $18 {What happened basically is that Black tried to attack and overpushed, created weaknesses and now it's even Black that's going to lose on the kingside} (17. g4 $18) *

