{[%evp 0,37,14,20,20,-11,38,-1,7,3,4,-18,-4,3,-7,0,0,-3,1,-8,19,-4,4,2,53,62,54,52,54,63,77,60,58,27,54,42,42,42,122,101] Artemiev Vladislav is a good Reti player. Study his games to learn the ideas and plans in this opening!} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. b3 Bg7 4. Bb2 O-O 5. g3 d6 6. Bg2 {This is a very instructive game from which you will learn many lines and typical ideas in the d6-e5 Reti.} e5 (6... c5 {Here White has 2 choices - to play d4 since Bg2 is already played, or to castle and allow e5 which will be studied later.} 7. O-O Nc6 {Same 2 choices again - d4 or d3 which allows e5} 8. d3) 7. d3 {Castling is also possible, e4 was not a threat but I would rather play d3 just to not think about it at all} Re8 8. O-O Nc6 9. Nc3 h6 $1 {Black wants to play Be6 and prevents Ng5} (9... Be6 $6 {Is not good because of} 10. Ng5 $1 h6 $2 (10... Bd7 {Now we can keep the knight on g5 for 1 or 2 moves, or we can withdraw to e4 immediately} 11. Nge4 (11. a3 {a3 is also a possible way for White to play} a5 12. e3) 11... Nxe4 12. dxe4 $1 {[%cal Gc3d5,Ge2e3] This is almost always a good move and a good pawn structure for White. Nd5 is coming, e3, White can play on both sides of the board} (12. Nxe4 {This move is also playable} f5 13. Nc3 g5 {Again, Black is starting to attack where there is no attack} 14. Nd5 h5 15. e3 g4 {Black has overextended on the kingside by pushing the pawns in front of the Black king, so White can consider taking over on the kingside} (15... h4 16. gxh4 $1 $18 {Such an idea is rare but it exists, although White needs to calculate before playing such a move, the idea is the following:} gxh4 $2 (16... Re6 17. hxg5 Qxg5 18. f4 $1 $18) 17. Kh1 $18 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gf1g1,Gg1g8,Gd1h5,Gf2f4,Gb2g7] With Rg1, Qh5, f4, White has a winning position}) 16. f3 (16. b4 {Playing on the queenside is also possible}) 16... gxf3 17. Bxf3 $18 {Qxf3 is also possible but it may run into e4, so Bxf3 is safer and better})) 11. Nxe6 fxe6 12. a3 d5 {Black's central pawn structure is not going anywhere} 13. e3 $1 (13. b4 {is also good}) 13... d4 14. Ne4 $18) (9... Nh5 10. Nd2 f5 {Again, White has different moves such as Nd5, a3, e3} 11. Nd5 f4 {[%cal Gc8g4]} 12. e3 $1 {Preventing Bg4!} (12. Ne4 $6 {Ne4 is tempting but it allows Bg4!} Bg4 $1 $132) 12... Be6 13. Ne4 Bxd5 $2 14. cxd5 Ne7 15. Ng5 $18 {[%csl Ge6]}) (9... e4 {Almost always e4 is not a good move, but White needs to take with the knight!} 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. dxe4 Rxe4 {[%csl Gc3,Gd5,Rf3][%cal Gf3c3,Gc3d5,Gf3d2,Gd2e4,Ge4c3]} 13. Nd2 $1 {The knight is going to be transferred to the c3 square and then to the d5 outpost. Theoretically Black can kick it away later with c6 but that would make the pawn on d6 weak} Re8 14. Ne4 {Nb1 with the same idea would be interesting but Black has Qf6 unfortunately} Bh3 {Is the computer's choice} (14... Bf5 15. Nc3 Qd7 16. Qd2 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gc3d5,Gd2c3,Gd2b2,Gb2g7] Nd5 is coming and checks from c3 or b2 can cause big problems for Black} Bh3 17. Nd5 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 $16 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gd2c3,Gd2b2,Gb2g7]}) 15. Nc3 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 $16 Qd7 17. e4 (17. Qd2 {is also possible}) 17... f5 18. exf5 Qxf5 19. Qd2 Ne5 20. f3 $16) 10. a3 $3 {White is not exactly on time to play Nd2 and Nd5 which after the trade on d5 would allow Nb4, that's why a3. Nd2 is also playable though} (10. Nd2 Be6 11. a3 (11. Nd5 $6 Bxd5 (11... Ne7 $2 12. Nxf6+ $18 {[%cal Gg2b7]}) (11... Rb8 12. a3 (12. e3 {is also playable} Ne7 13. Nxf6+ Bxf6 14. b4) 12... Ne7 13. Nxf6+ Bxf6 14. b4 (14. d4 exd4 15. Ne4 $16 Nf5 $2 16. Nxf6+ Qxf6 17. e4 $1 $18) 14... d5 15. cxd5 Nxd5 16. Qc2 $16) 12. cxd5 Ne7 $2 (12... Nb4 $1 {This is playable for White as there is compensation for the pawn, but it may not be to everyone's taste. I would prefer not to enter this especially since I have another good option - 10.a3} 13. e4 Nxd3 14. Bc3 Nc5 15. b4 Ncd7 $44) 13. e4 Nd7 14. Rc1 f5 15. Qc2 $16 (15. f4 {Can be also considered, Black has a weaker king})) 11... d5 12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. Rc1 $3 Nxc3 14. Rxc3 Bd5 (14... e4 15. Nxe4 $16) 15. Bxd5 Qxd5 16. Rc4 Rad8 17. b4 a6 18. Qc2 f5 19. Nb3 $16) 10... Be6 (10... a5 11. Nd2 $1 Be6 12. Nd5 Rb8 13. Rb1 Ne7 14. Nxf6+ $1 Bxf6 15. d4 $3 (15. b4 axb4 16. axb4 c6 $6 17. Ne4 Bg7 18. c5 $1 d5 19. Nd6 Rf8 20. f4) 15... exd4 16. Ne4 Bg7 17. Bxd4 Nc6 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Nc3 $14 Kh7 20. Qd2 Ne5 21. f4 $16) (10... Kh7 {The idea is to show how White would proceed} 11. Nd2 {Now with a3, there would be no Nb4 after Be6 Nd5 Nxd5 cxd5} Be6 12. Nd5 Rb8 13. e3 Ne7 14. Nxf6+ {White wants to take the f6 knight since it was better placed than the one on e7} Bxf6 15. b4 d5 16. cxd5 Nxd5 17. Rc1 $14 {[%cal Gd2e4,Ge4c5,Gc1c7] White has simple moves while Black doesn't have a good plan in this position}) 11. b4 $1 d5 $2 {This is why White kept his knight on f3} (11... Qd7 12. b5 (12. Nd2) 12... Nd8 13. a4 Bh3 14. a5) 12. b5 $3 (12. cxd5 $1 Nxd5 13. Rc1 $14 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gc3e4,Gc3a4,Ga4c5,Ge4c5]} Nxc3 14. Bxc3 a6 15. Nd2 Bd5 16. Bxd5 Qxd5 17. Qb3 $1 Qxb3 18. Nxb3 {These positions without the queens on the board are very good for White. White can play Nc5 or a4-b5, White has good control over the c file} Rac8 (18... Nd4 19. Bxd4 exd4 $16 {White can take on c7 but also good is defending with Rc2. The knight puts pressure on d4 and White has good control of the c file where White can even double and protect the weakness on e2 with the king, so White has a very comfortable position}) 19. e3 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gg1f1,Gf1e2] With Rac8 Black defended c7 and may want to jump Nd4, Rfe1 is possible, e3 is another good move - it's not weakening d3 much as the next moves can be Rfd1, Kf1-Ke2, bringing the king closer to the center}) 12... Na5 13. Nxe5 $16 {The position will become extremely sharp and tactical, although it works out well for White, it may not be to everyone's taste, that's why 12.cxd5 is a playable alternative} dxc4 14. Qa4 Nd5 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. Nxf7 $3 Kxf7 (16... Bxf7 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Qxa5 $18) 17. Bxd5+ Qxd5 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Qxa5 $18 1-0

