{[%evp 0,131,14,-6,-11,-63,16,-44,-39,-32,-35,-32,-3,-2,-10,3,-2,-8,-3,0,7,5,8,13,33,40,30,35,69,44,51,34,106,39,59,24,24,26,30,15,52,35,44,14,40,40,22,22,22,-1,17,5,18,17,18,11,60,44,45,41,77,90,71,71,69,64,64,70,78,84,84,91,93,110,114,119,104,95,95,118,85,85,100,94,83,95,102,102,107,51,63,29,75,84,122,106,109,109,134,186,193,139,160,181,158,172,179,187,187,187,187,185,185,185,163,164,154,202,213,213,213,205,231,240,245,244,238,226,214,257,313,485,485,187]} 1. c4 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. b3 e5 4. Bb2 Nc6 5. Nf3 d6 6. Bg2 Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. d3 Re8 9. Nc3 {We can get this position from various move orders} Nd4 $5 ({We already covered} 9... e4 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. dxe4 Rxe4 13. Nd2 Re8 14. Ne4 Bh3 (14... Bd7 15. Nc3) 15. Nc3 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd1d2,Gd2b2,Gd2c3,Gc3d5]}) 10. Nd2 {[%cal Ge2e3] The next move is e3} c6 (10... Bg4 11. h3) 11. e3 Nf5 12. Nde4 h5 (12... Nxe4 {This is almost never good} 13. dxe4 Ne7 14. Qd2 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gd1d6,Gb2a3,Ga3d6] White has great control over the center and can put pressure on the weak d6 pawn. Ba3 may even force c5 and create additional weaknesses}) 13. h3 {The idea is to meet h5-h4 with g3-g4!} (13. Nxf6+ {Is also good} Bxf6 14. b4 {intending b5} Be6 (14... h4 15. b5 c5 {With this Black closes the queenside and wants to attack on the kingside. After a4-a5, Black will play Rb8 and prepare to close the queenside completely. The engine here would give a big plus for White due to the space advantage, but when playing this position, the positional characteristics such as the d5 outpost and the plan that White can attack on the kingside matter too - f4 should be on White's mind later, not now since Black is well organized, White needs to improve the position first.} 16. Nd5 Bg7 17. a4 hxg3 18. hxg3 Nh6 19. Qd2 f5 20. f4 $16) 15. b5 Rc8 16. Rc1 $14 d5 $4 17. bxc6 bxc6 18. cxd5 cxd5 19. Nxd5 $18) 13... Nh7 14. b4 Be6 15. b5 c5 $2 (15... d5 $6 16. Nc5 $16) 16. Nd5 {Now a potential idea after Black pushes f5 can be Nec3} (16. a4 Rb8 17. a5 Ne7 18. Re1 f5 19. Nd2 Nf6 20. f4 $16) 16... Ne7 (16... Bxd5 17. cxd5 {Black managed to trade the strong knight and eliminate the outpost for White on d5, but also created an outpost on c4 which White can use in the long run. Additionally, any f5-f4 will open up the position for White's bishop pair}) 17. Nec3 $14 Nxd5 18. Nxd5 Qd7 (18... f5 19. Qd2 {[%cal Gf2f4]} (19. f4 $6 {Unfortunately doesn't work tactically} exf4 20. Bxg7 Kxg7 $2 (20... Bxd5 $1 $11) 21. Nxf4 Rb8 22. Qd2 $16)) 19. Kh2 Ng5 20. h4 Nh7 21. Rb1 Bg4 22. Qd2 Nf6 23. Nxf6+ Bxf6 24. Bd5 Be6 25. Bxe6 Qxe6 26. e4 Bg7 27. f4 exf4 28. Rxf4 Bxb2 29. Qxb2 Qe5 30. Qf2 Re7 31. Rf1 Rf8 32. Rf6 Kg7 33. Kg2 Rd7 34. a4 Qe7 35. a5 Qe5 36. Qf3 Qe7 37. Rf2 Rh8 38. Qf4 Rh7 39. e5 Qxe5 (39... dxe5 40. Rxf7+) 40. Rxf7+ Rxf7 41. Qxf7+ Kh6 42. Qf8+ Rg7 43. Qh8+ Rh7 44. Qxe5 dxe5 45. Rf8 Rd7 46. Rb8 g5 47. Kf2 Kg6 48. Ke3 Rg7 49. Ra8 gxh4 50. gxh4 b6 51. axb6 axb6 52. Rb8 Kf5 53. Rxb6 Rg3+ 54. Kd2 e4 55. Rd6 Rg2+ 56. Ke3 Rg3+ 57. Kd2 Rg2+ 58. Ke3 Rg3+ 59. Kf2 Rf3+ 60. Ke2 Rh3 61. Rd5+ Kf4 62. dxe4 Kxe4 63. Rxc5 Rh2+ 64. Ke1 Rxh4 65. b6 Kd4 66. Rc7 1-0

