{[%evp 0,39,14,20,20,-11,11,4,4,10,13,2,2,2,2,-5,1,10,29,33,40,20,11,31,28,12,3,5,41,50,34,54,54,54,84,82,129,129,129,85,85,101]} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. b3 {Is another move order for Whte. Black can also play Nc6 and e6 here} g6 (3... d6 {The main position can arise from different move orders} 4. Bb2 e5 5. d3 Nc6 6. g3 g6 7. Bg2 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Nc3) 4. Bb2 Nc6 5. g3 Bg7 (5... d6 6. Bg2 (6. d4 {Not yet as White hasn't played Bg2. White would need to be careful of ideas such as Ne4 and potentially some check Qa5}) 6... e5 7. d3 Qa5+ 8. Nfd2 $1 Bg7 9. O-O O-O 10. Nc3 Be6 11. a3 Qd8 12. Nd5) 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O d6 (7... d5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Bxg7 Kxg7 10. d4 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 (11... e6 $6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Qc2 $16) 12. Qxd4+ Nf6 13. Qe5 $16) 8. d3 $1 {d4 was also possible but we are not afraid of Black's set-up c5-d6-e5} e5 (8... Bd7 9. Nc3 Re8 10. a3 e5 11. Nd2 a6 12. e3 (12. b4 $16) 12... h5 13. Nde4 Be6 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Nd5 Bg7 16. b4 cxb4 17. axb4 Bxd5 18. Bxd5 Nxb4 19. Bxb7 Rb8 20. Bg2 Nxd3 21. Qxd3 Rxb2 22. Rxa6 $14) 9. Nc3 {[%cal Ga2a3,Gf3d2] a3 and Nd2 are next} h6 {Preparing Be6 (preventing Ng5)} (9... Be6 10. Ng5 Bd7 11. Nge4 Ne8 {[%cal Gf7f5] Black wants to play f5 and kick our knight away from e4, so we create a square for it on c3} (11... Nxe4 12. dxe4 $16 {Taking with the pawn is better, targeting the weak pawn on d6} (12. Nxe4 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge4c3,Gc3d5] is also playable} Be6 13. Nc3 $14)) 12. Nd5 f5 13. Nec3 {[%cal Ga2a3,Gb3b4,Ge2e3]} h5 14. e3 h4 15. a3 a5 16. Rb1 {Again, it's not easy for Black to make progress} g5 $2 17. Qh5 $18 (17. gxh4 $18 {We see this idea again, Black has overextended on the kingside and now we can use that to our advantage} gxh4 18. Kh1 {[%cal Gf1g1,Gg1g8]} (18. f4 exf4 19. Nxf4 Nf6 20. Ncd5 $18))) (9... Nh5 10. Nd2 (10. Nd5 $2 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gg7b2,Ge5e4,Rc3d5] Be careful of e4!} e4 $19) 10... f5 11. Nd5 Nf6 (11... f4 12. e3 {Preventing Bg4} (12. Ne4 Bg4) 12... fxe3 (12... Be6 13. Ne4 $16) 13. fxe3 Qg5 (13... Be6 14. Rxf8+ $16) 14. Rxf8+ {This is a general chess idea when the opponent can't recapture with the rook, a move like Rxf8 is good! Black will need to either expose the king or misplace the bishop to recapture} Bxf8 15. Ne4 $18) (11... g5 12. e3 {[%cal Gd1h5]} g4 13. f3 {We need to play f3 to break down Black's structure and open our pieces} (13. a3 f4 14. f3 fxg3) 13... gxf3 14. Qxf3 {Be careful of e4, it's not working here for Black though} Nf6 (14... e4 15. Qxh5 Bxb2 16. Rab1 $18) 15. Qe2 Be6 16. e4 (16. a3 {a3 b4 is also possible}) 16... Bxd5 $2 17. cxd5 $18) 12. e3 Be6 (12... h5 13. f4 $16 exf4 14. gxf4 Be6 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. Bxc6 $3 (17. Nf3 $16) 17... bxc6 18. Nf3 $16) 13. a3 Rb8 14. Rb1 (14. b4 $14) 14... Ne7 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. b4 (16. f4 exf4 17. Bxf6 Rxf6 18. gxf4 $16) 16... h5 17. f4 exf4 18. Bxf6 Rxf6 19. gxf4 b6 20. Nf3 $16) (9... Ne8 10. Nd2 (10. Ne1 Nc7 (10... f5 11. Nc2 f4 12. e3 Be6 (12... Nc7)) 11. Nc2 Be6 12. Ne3) 10... f5 11. Nd5 g5 (11... f4 12. e3 g5 13. Ne4 $1 g4 14. exf4 (14. f3 $1 gxf3 15. Qxf3 fxe3 16. Qxe3 $18) 14... exf4 15. Bxg7 Nxg7 16. Nxf4 Nd4 17. Re1 $18) 12. e3 g4 13. a3 Nf6 (13... h5 14. f3 $1 $16) 14. b4 $16) (9... Re8 10. a3 $1 {[%cal Gf3d2] The same goes if the pawn is on c5 (in the other games earlier it was on c7), we calculate - Nd2, Be6, Nd5, Bxd5, cxd5 and Black has Nb4 and on e4, defending the d5 pawn, Black can take Nxd3. That's why White goes a3} (10. Nd2 $1 {The computer says this variation is playable, but logic says it loses a pawn, continuing the variation makes Nd2 playable though} Be6 11. a3 $1 (11. Nd5 Bxd5 12. cxd5 Nb4 13. e4 Nxd3 14. Bc3 b5 15. Qe2 b4 16. Qxd3 bxc3 17. Nc4 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Gd3c3,Gg2h3,Gc4a5]}) 11... d5 12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. Rc1) (10. Ng5 $6 h6 (10... Nh5 $1) 11. Nge4 Nh7 12. Nd5 f5 13. Nec3 Nf6 (13... Bd7 14. Nb5) 14. a3 $16) 10... h6 {Now we are on time with Nd2} (10... Be6 11. Ng5 Bd7 12. e3 {or Nge4 directly} h6 13. Nge4 Nxe4 14. dxe4 $16 (14. Nxe4 {is also playable but dxe4 is better} Be6 15. Nc3 $14 {[%cal Ge4c3,Gc3d5]} f5 16. Nd5 g5 17. b4 g4 18. Rb1 h5 19. f3 $18)) 11. Nd2 Be6 (11... Bd7 {There is a difference when the bishop is not on e6, we don't really want to play Nd5. It's not a bad move, but Black can take it with Nxd5 and it will be okay for Black. With the bishop on e6, Nxd5 is not possible due to cxd5 which will be a fork. So now we can continue with normal moves such as a3, Rb1 or e3} 12. e3) 12. Nd5 Qd7 13. e3 (13. b4 $5 cxb4 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. axb4 Nxb4 16. Ne4 Bg7 17. Ba3 a5 18. Qb3 $14) 13... Rac8 (13... Bxd5 $2 14. cxd5 Ne7 15. e4 $16) (13... Ne7 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. b4 {White is already threatening bxc5 and Ne4 double attack on Bf6 and the c5 pawn} Bg7 16. Rb1) 14. Rb1 Bh3 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Ne4 Be7 17. Bxh3 Qxh3 18. Nc3 Qd7 19. Nd5 f5 20. b4 Bd8 21. Qd2 (21. f4 {was also possible}) 21... Qf7 22. f4 Bf6 23. e4 Nd4 24. bxc5 dxc5 25. Bxd4 exd4 (25... cxd4 26. fxe5) 26. e5 Bg7 27. Qg2 b6 28. a4 $18) 10. a3 {Again, the line Nd2 Be6 Nd5 Bxd5 cxd5 Black would have Nb4, so White goes a3 first} Be6 11. Nd2 $1 d5 {This is a concrete variation which we need to know} (11... Qd7 12. Nd5 Nh7 13. Rb1 f5 14. e3 g5 15. b4 g4 16. f4 gxf3 (16... exf4 17. Nxf4 $16) 17. Nxf3 $16) 12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. Rc1 $1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc1c8]} Nxc3 (13... b6 $6 14. b4 $1 cxb4 $4 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. e4 Be6 17. Rxc6 $18) (13... Nde7 14. Na4 b6 15. b4 $16 {[%csl Rc5]} f5 (15... cxb4 16. Bxc6 Nxc6 17. Rxc6 Bh3 {[%cal Gd8d5,Gd5c6,Gd5g2]} 18. Qb3 Bxf1 19. Nxf1 $16 bxa3 20. Bxa3 Re8 21. Rxg6 $18) 16. bxc5 b5 17. Nc3 a6 18. Re1 Rc8 19. Qc2 Qd7 20. Qb1 g5 21. Qa1 $14) 14. Rxc3 $1 Qe7 (14... e4 $2 15. Nxe4 Bxc3 16. Bxc3 {[%cal Ge4f6,Ge4c5] White has a winning position already} f6 17. Nxc5 Bc8 18. b4 $18) 15. Bxc6 $1 bxc6 16. Qc2 {[%csl Rc5,Rc6]} e4 17. Nxe4 Bxc3 18. Qxc3 f6 19. Nxc5 (19. Nxf6+ Rxf6 20. Qxf6 Qxf6 21. Bxf6 Bxb3 22. Rc1 Re8 23. Kf1 $18) 19... Bh3 20. Re1 $16 {White is much better, strategically winning. The White king is not going to be checkmated, while the Black king is weak, there is a potential Qc4+ and transferring the queen to the kingside. Additionally, all the White pieces are well placed.} *

