{[%evp 0,33,14,20,20,-11,30,4,3,4,5,-2,-2,-3,1,1,24,-1,32,14,17,-5,15,8,51,46,76,21,21,9,20,60,34,11,16,63]} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 (2... c5 3. b3 Nc6 4. Bb2 g6 (4... d6 5. g3 e5 6. d3 g6 7. Bg2 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Nc3) 5. g3 Bg7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O d6 8. d3 e5 9. Nc3 Re8 10. a3 h6 (10... e4 {Is almost never good, White almost always takes with the knight!} 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. dxe4 Rxe4 {And now the knight from f3 needs to get to c3 and then perhaps to jump on d5} 14. Nd2 Re8 15. Ne4 $16) 11. Nd2 Nh7 12. e3 f5 13. Nd5 Bd7 14. b4 Rb8 15. Rb1 Nf6 16. Bc3 {White is intending at some moment to take on c3 and a possible plan is to prepare and play f4!} Nxd5 17. cxd5 Ne7 18. b5 {b5 is playable but not the best (White had other moves such as bxc5 or Nc4). This shows the idea of how we can create the c4 square as an outpost for the White knight} g5 19. Nc4 Nc8 20. a4 {We have great control over the position and we can also wait a bit for Black's play in order to start our counterplay, for example:} g4 $6 21. f3 $18) 3. b3 Bg7 4. Bb2 d6 5. g3 O-O 6. Bg2 e5 7. O-O Nbd7 {We will follow the same plan with White - d3, Nc3, Nd2 and so on} 8. d3 Re8 9. Nc3 $1 c6 10. Rc1 $1 {In the c6-d6-Nbd7 set-up, I will play Nc3, e3 and Rc1! The idea is to meet d5 with cxd5 and then Ne2, Rc2! and Qa1!! First e3 and then Rc1 was also possible} a6 {Intending d5 and after cxd5 cxd5, Nb5 won't be possible} (10... d5 11. cxd5 cxd5 $2 (11... Nxd5 12. e3 $14 {The knight on d7 is misplaced} N7f6 13. Na4 $14) 12. Nb5 $18 {[%csl Gc1,Rc7][%cal Gb5c7,Gc7e8,Gc7a8,Ga1c1,Gc1c8]}) (10... h6 11. e3 (11. b4 {Is also playable}) 11... a6 12. b4 (12. d4 {is not a move White would like to play because it allows e4} e4 13. Nd2 d5) 12... d5 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Ne2 {[%cal Gc1c2,Gd1a1]} e4 15. dxe4 dxe4 16. Nd2 {[%csl Gd2,Gd4] We already saw the typical idea of this knight going to d4, leaving the d4 square free for the other knight}) 11. e3 d5 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Ne2 $1 {[%csl Ga1,Gb2,Re5][%cal Gc1c2,Gd1a1,Ga1h8,Gf1c1]} b6 14. Rc2 $1 Bb7 15. Qa1 $14 e4 (15... Qe7 $2 16. Rc7 $18) 16. dxe4 dxe4 17. Nd2 $1 {Nfd4 is natural but Nd2 is better because the other knight will go to d4, while the knight from d2 puts pressure on e4 and can later go to c4 which is also a good square for the knight} 1-0

