{[%evp 0,9,20,20,75,33,64,30,30,30,68,46]} 1. Nf3 {From the rare set-ups, the most common are the Romanishin variation and the Dutch.} f5 {Against the Dutch, White goes d3! and e4! which is a very dangerous set-up to meet for Black.} (1... Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 a6 {The so-called Romanishin system. It is risky but playable. The idea is to play b5 and Bb7, to solve the problem of the c8 bishop.} 4. Bg2 b5 5. b3 {White didn't have any good tactics on the long diagonal. White wants to castle and play naturally, but also to try and take advantage of the a6-b5 advance. After 5... Bb7 6.Nc3! the game takes a positional character, while after 5...c5 6.Nc3! or 6.0-0 and 7.Nc3! we play tactically!}) 2. d3 {In this d3-e4 set-up, the moves White wants to play are 3.e4, 4.exf5! and 5.d3-d4! with a good open position and weak Black king!} d6 (2... Nf6 $6 3. e4 d6 (3... fxe4 $6 {Accepting the pawn sacrifice can be very dangerous for Black.}) 4. exf5 Bxf5 5. d4 $1 {And White has a good game.}) 3. e4 e5 4. Nc3 $1 {Now we are ready to take exf5! and after that to play d4!} c5 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gc5d4,Ge5d4,Rd3d4] Black prevents d4 but in return weakens the d5 square.} 5. g3 $1 $14 {This is an idea to remember, next is Bh3! or Nh4! and Black will lose control over the light squares.} *

