1. Nf3 f5 $6 {Against the Dutch we go d3! and e4! This is a very good set-up against the Dutch and there is a good chance that it may catch your opponents unprepared. In any case, with the best moves from both sides, White gets an advantage.} 2. d3 $1 {In this d3-e4 set-up, the moves White wants to play are 3.e4, 4.exf5! and 5.d3-d4! with a good open position and weak Black king!} d6 $1 (2... d5 {Black just weakened the e5 square permanently, we can play many moves like c4 for example, but I really like:} 3. d4 $1 {With a good version of the stonewall dutch} Nf6 (3... c5 4. c4 $16) 4. Bf4 e6 5. e3 Bd6 6. c4 c6 (6... Bxf4 7. exf4 {[%csl Re6][%cal Ge1e6] We are not worried at all about this capture as the pawn on e6 becomes very weak.}) 7. Nbd2 {The knight is better placed here as he has a quicker route to c5 - either through f3 or through c4 if the pawns c and d pawns are traded} (7. Nc3 {[%cal Rc3d5,Rc3b5,Rc3e4,Gd5e4,Gc6b5,Gc6d5] This is natural but not the best for White. The e5 square is an outpost and the knight will require 4 moves to get there from c3. Additionally, the Black pawns are blocking the knight to jump forward.}) 7... O-O 8. Bd3 $16 {Black avoided the Reti but got in a much worse position.}) (2... Nf6 $6 3. e4 $1 {White sacrifices a pawn for the initiative!} d6 (3... fxe4 $6 4. dxe4 Nxe4 5. Nbd2 $1 {In my view, this might be even better than Bd3.} (5. Bd3 {Is also good.} Nf6 $6 (5... d5 6. O-O $14) 6. Ng5 $1 {[%cal Gg5h7,Gd3h7] Nxh7 and Bxh7 are threats at the moment.}) 5... Nxd2 6. Bxd2 {With a quick development.} d5 (6... Nc6 7. Bd3 $16 {Black needs to be careful of Ng5.}) 7. c4 e6 8. Bd3 Be7 9. Ne5 $18) 4. exf5 Bxf5 5. d4 $1 {White's main idea has been executed, and now White has a good position.} e6 6. Bd3 (6. Bb5+ {The best move according to the engine - White wants to provoke c6 and then come back to d3. This idea would take the c6 square away for the Black knight on b8.} Nbd7 (6... c6 7. Bd3 Be7 8. O-O $16 {White should think about Re1, Bxf5 or even Ng5 next.}) 7. O-O $16) 6... Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 $16 (8. Bxf5 $16)) (2... Nc6 $5 3. d4 $1 $14 {In this opening quite often after playing d3, we need to be ready to play d4!} (3. g3 $2 {This doesn't put any pressure on Black and it allows him to develop naturally and get the center.} e5 4. Bg2 (4. c4 $6 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 $15) 4... Nf6 $36 5. c4 g6 6. O-O Bg7 7. Nc3 O-O 8. b3 d6 9. Bb2 {It's not the same position from the d6-e5 set-ups since Black is 2 tempos up. In those set-ups Black should move the knight, play f5, and then potentially get the knight back to f6, here f5 was played in one move and the knight is already on f6.}) (3. e4 e5 {This was the idea of Nc6, to play e5 and it would be something like a reversed King's Gambit, Black will have compensation for the pawn} 4. exf5 d5 {This is not our goal of what we want to reach since now Black will have the initiative}) (3. c4 $2 e5 {Black's ambitious opening went unpunished. When playing the Reti, we need to keep an open mind and sometimes we can turn the position in an advantageous d4 system!}) 3... e6 4. g3 (4. c4 {Is possible but perhaps there is no need to give Black a chance to exchange the bishop, we can go for castling first.} Bb4+) 4... Nf6 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. c4 $14 {White has a comfortable position, the knight on c6 is misplaced in this version of the Dutch. White will have d5 ideas in mind to break down Black's central structure (after a potential d6 for example).}) (2... a6 {This is just an example which demonstrates White's idea well.} 3. e4 d6 4. exf5 Bxf5 5. d4 {It's like we are playing a 1.e4 opening where f5 only created weaknesses in Black's position.} Nf6 {White is better with any normal moves such as Bd3, Be2 or even g3 and Bg2.} 6. Bd3 $16) 3. e4 e5 (3... Nc6 4. exf5 Bxf5 5. d4 $1 Nb4 6. Na3 $16 {[%cal Gc2c3] White will first kick the knight away with c3 and then will play standard moves like Bd3, 0-0, Re1 with advantage.}) (3... g6 4. exf5 (4. h4 $5) 4... Bxf5 5. d4 $16) 4. Nc3 $1 {Now we are threatening to take on f5 and then to play d4!} (4. exf5 {The idea of playing d6 and e5 is that Black wants to get a playable position after exf5, for example} Bxf5 5. d4 e4 $13) 4... c5 $5 {Black took firm control over the d4 square so we can't play our usual plan of exf5 and d4, however, the downside of c5 is that now the light squares, especially d5, are even weaker. Now, when we can't go exf5 and d4, we need to remember the idea of g3! and Bh3!} (4... Nc6 5. exf5 Bxf5 6. d4 $1 Nxd4 (6... e4 {is not working now because we have} 7. d5 $1 exf3 8. dxc6 bxc6 9. Qxf3 $16 Qd7 $6 10. Bb5 $1 Ne7 11. Ba4 $18) 7. Nxd4 exd4 8. Qxd4 c6 (8... Bxc2 $2 9. Bc4 $16) 9. g4 $1 Bxc2 10. Bf4 $36) (4... fxe4 5. dxe4 Nf6 6. Bc4 $16) 5. g3 $1 Nc6 {Now White has a choice of two good moves - Bh3 and Nh4} 6. Bh3 $1 (6. Nh4 $5) 6... fxe4 7. Bxc8 Qxc8 8. dxe4 $14 {[%csl Gd5] The d5 square is weak, we will try to exchange the pieces guarding that square. It doesn't matter that we don't have a light-squared bishop as Black also doesn't have a light-squared bishop. White has a good position.} *

