1. Nf3 f5 2. d3 Nf6 (2... Nc6 3. d4 $3) 3. e4 d5 $6 (3... Nc6 $6 4. e5 Nd5 5. d4 d6 6. e6 $5 (6. c4 Nb6 7. e6 d5 8. c5 $18) 6... Nb6 7. d5 Nb4 8. c4 c6 9. Nc3 $18) (3... d6 4. exf5 Bxf5 5. d4 $14 {With an easy advantage for White.}) 4. exf5 {From all the normal options White had such as exd5 or e5, this is probably the worst one but it's still good for White.} (4. e5 $1 Nfd7 5. d4 e6 6. c4 $16 (6. Ng5 $5) 6... dxc4 7. Bxc4 Nb6 8. Bb3 Nd5 9. O-O Be7 10. Nc3 $16) (4. exd5 c6 (4... Nxd5 5. d4 $16) 5. c4 (5. d4 cxd5 6. c4 $16 {This is possible, something like a Panov where the pawn is on f5 which is a better version for White.}) (5. dxc6 {Taking the pawn is also possible but we need to be careful to not allow Black any activity, practically there is no need to take the pawn.} Nxc6 6. d4 $16 (6. g3 $2 {Would allow Black a lot of activity for the pawn.} e5)) 5... cxd5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. d4 $16 {White is having an isolated pawn but a very good version of it. Besides the space and activity the isolated pawn allows, the move f5 created weaknesses in the Black territory such as the e5 square and the weak e pawn on which we can put pressure later.}) 4... Bxf5 5. d4 e6 6. Bd3 Bd6 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 Ne4 9. Nbd2 c5 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Bxe4 Nc6 12. d5 exd5 13. Qxd5+ Kh8 14. Bg5 Bxe4 15. Qxe4 Qc7 16. Rad1 h6 17. Qg6 Bf4 18. Bxf4 Qxf4 19. Rd7 Rf6 20. Qxg7# 1-0

