1. Nf3 (1. d4 f5 2. h3 {The idea is similar to this version of the Dutch.} Nf6 3. g4 fxg4 (3... d5 4. Nf3 e6 5. gxf5 exf5 $11) (3... e6 4. Nf3 d5 5. c4 c6 6. Nc3 Bd6 7. Bg2 O-O $11 8. g5 $6 Ne4 $15) 4. hxg4 Nxg4 5. e4 d6 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gc1g5,Gf1e2]} 6. Bg5 $16) 1... f5 2. h3 $5 {Is an interesting idea that involves a pawn sacrifice after g4 and if Black accepts it, it will be a really tough position for Black. However, this is not my recommendation as there is no need for Black to accept it, and in that case, Black can get a normal position from the opening where White has played h3-g4, and those tempi could have been spent on doing something more useful.} (2. d3 {The difference with this gambit (d3-e4) is that even if Black doesn't accept it, White has a good position.} Nf6 3. e4 d6 4. exf5 Bxf5 5. d4 $14) 2... d6 (2... Nf6 3. g4 (3. d4 e6 4. g4 d5 $11) 3... fxg4 (3... d5 $11) 4. hxg4 Nxg4 $16 {[%cal Gd2d4,Ge2e4] White can gain space and activity by pushing the central pawns and perhaps later also taking some tempi by attacking the knight, while the Black king has been weakened by the f5 push. White has a nice position here, but again, Black doesn't need to take the g4 pawn.}) 3. g4 fxg4 4. hxg4 Bxg4 5. d4 Bxf3 6. exf3 e5 7. Bd3 Qf6 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. Ne4 Qe7 10. d5 Nd8 11. Bg5 Nf6 12. f4 Nf7 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Bb5+ Kd8 15. Qh5 a6 16. Bd3 Bh6 17. f5 Kc8 18. Ke2 Kb8 19. Qf3 Ka7 20. Rxh6 Nxh6 21. Qe3+ b6 22. Qxh6 Raf8 23. a4 Qf7 24. a5 b5 25. c4 Rb8 26. b3 bxc4 27. Bxc4 Qf8 28. Qe3+ Kb7 29. Rc1 Ra8 30. Bd3 h5 31. Rc6 h4 32. Nxd6+ Kb8 33. Rb6+ cxb6 34. Qxb6# *

