{[%evp 0,57,20,20,20,6,6,-28,-7,12,22,-8,30,17,69,60,44,7,29,-3,22,38,61,36,89,74,74,51,75,69,82,80,147,90,104,132,224,226,225,215,488,488,448,387,395,209,247,251,239,245,329,334,369,341,341,390,405,308,308,329]} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 a6 $5 {The so-called Romanishin system. It is risky but playable. The idea is to play b5 and Bb7, to solve the problem of the c8 bishop.} 4. Bg2 b5 5. b3 $1 {White didn't have any good tactics on the long diagonal. White wants to castle and play naturally, but also to try and take advantage of the a6-b5 advance. After 5...Bb7 6.Nc3! the game takes a positional character, while after 5...c5 6.Nc3! or 6.0-0 and 7.Nc3! we play tactically!} c5 {Black's idea is to keep flexibility on the queenside. If Nc3, Black doesn't want to play b4 due to Na4, so Black wants to play Qb6 to defend the b5 pawn.} (5... Bb7 6. Nc3 $1 {Forcing Black to do something about the b5 pawn.} b4 (6... Bb4 $5 {Is possibly even the best move in this position. We will see some games with this move.}) 7. Na4 {The knight is on the edge of the board but as we will see, the knight can be useful there if the battle takes over on the queenside or if it can coordinate with the rest of the White pieces.} c5 $6 {This would be a wrong move because now the knight automatically puts pressure on the c5 pawn and the b6 square has been weakened and may become available for the knight in the future.} (7... Be7 8. Bb2 O-O 9. O-O $14 {[%cal Gd2d4]})) 6. Nc3 Qb6 {The downside of this move is that it's losing some time.} 7. O-O Bb7 8. Re1 $1 {[%cal Ge2e4] Intending to go e4 quickly and then e5 or pushing d4 is also an idea.} ({If White starts playing passive moves, Black will achieve his goals. For example:} 8. d3 Be7 9. Bb2 d6 10. e4 Nc6 11. Re1 O-O 12. Rb1 Nd7 $15 {[%cal Ge7f6] White didn't play actively to use the lead in development, so playing passively for several moves can give Black a comfortable position.}) 8... d6 $2 {Is too slow. Black should play Be7 instead.} (8... Be7 $1 {This might be the best for Black which leads to a playable position.} 9. e4 O-O $1 10. e5 Ne8 11. d4 $5 $14) (8... Ne4 $6 9. Bb2 Nxc3 10. Bxc3 $36) 9. e4 Be7 (9... Nc6 $6 10. Nd5 $1 {It's more of a positional sacrifice, White is not winning by force but has great initiative and compensation.} exd5 11. exd5+ Ne7 12. Bb2 $18) 10. d4 $1 $16 cxd4 11. Nxd4 {Black is close to losing in this position.} b4 (11... bxc4 {This is not a solution since after} 12. bxc4 {[%cal Ga1b1,Yb1b7] With Rb1 coming, there may be also some sacrifices like Rxb7 and/or e5.}) 12. Na4 $6 $16 {Na4 is not as good as Nd5! although White still has a big advantage.} (12. Nd5 $3 exd5 13. exd5 $18 {Again, more of a positional sacrifice. Most of the time there is no forced win. Defending this with Black is almost impossible!} Bc8 {Controlling the f5 square so White doesn't have Nf5.} (13... Kf8 14. Nf5 Bd8 {White has tremendous compensation and initiative. Many moves are good, Bf4 is one, Be3 is another and so on.} 15. Bf4 Bc7 {Again, many moves are winning: Re7 with the idea Rxc7, Qd2 with the idea Bh6, c5! immediately also wins.} 16. Re7 $18) 14. Bf4 $36) 12... Qc7 13. Bd2 {White took advantage of all those slow moves like a6, b5, and managed to open the center.} Nc6 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. Bxb4 Qb7 16. Bxd6 Rd8 17. c5 Bxe4 18. Rxe4 Nxe4 19. Qg4 f5 20. Qxg7 Rf8 21. Qxh7 Rd7 22. Nb6 Bxd6 23. Nxd7 Qxd7 24. Qg6+ Kd8 25. cxd6 Qxd6 26. Bxe4 Qd4 27. Qg5+ Kd7 28. Re1 fxe4 29. Qe3 {Kelires, A 2509 - Papadopoulos, A 2203 1-0} *

