1. c4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 a6 4. Bg2 b5 5. b3 c5 6. O-O Bb7 7. Nc3 Qb6 8. e3 ({Our choice is} 8. Re1 $1 {in this position.}) 8... d6 9. Qe2 {The idea of this game is to see the classical handling of the position as Black does play b4 later.} Bc6 10. d4 b4 11. Na4 {After Bxa4, bxa4, Black will have tactical problems.} Qb7 {We started with a tactical version of the opening but we ended up in a positional version of the opening. What White needs to do here is exchange light-squared bishops.} 12. Bb2 Nbd7 13. Nh4 Be7 14. Bxc6 Qxc6 15. Rad1 Qc7 16. e4 $5 (16. dxc5 dxc5 {Black could also take with the knight, but just to show that even this is better for White. The knight on a4 puts pressure on c5 and can sometimes, later on, jump on the b6 square.}) 16... cxd4 17. Bxd4 O-O 18. Nf3 {White has a nice hedgehog position. The knight on a4 is a good piece now and White has ideas such as pushing e5, where if the d6 pawn is exchanged, c4 will also become a passed pawn. That's the reason why Black plays:} e5 19. Bb2 Qc6 20. Rfe1 Bd8 {What White needs to do in this position is improve the knight from f3. The goal can be the d5 square so the knight needs to go to e3, there are several routes to get there.} 21. Qd3 Bc7 22. Nh4 $1 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gh4f5] The knight is threatening to go to f5 and e3.} g6 {[%cal Gg6f5]} 23. Bc1 {Improving the bishop.} Rfd8 24. Bg5 {Black can hardly move in this position} Nc5 25. Qf3 $18 Ncxe4 1-0

