1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 a6 4. Bg2 b5 5. b3 Bb7 {The positional version. The tactical version is with c5.} 6. Nc3 b4 7. Na4 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. d4 a5 10. Bg5 {White wants to exchange the dark-squared bishop for the f6 knight and then trade the light-squared bishops, after that White will stay with a knight against the bad bishop on f6.} Na6 (10... h6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. e3 {White consolidates the position and now the next step will be to trade the light-squared bishops.} d6 13. Ne1 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 {Taking with the king might be better since the knight won't be doing anything on g2, so it can go to d3 and then push the pawn to f4.}) 11. Ne5 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 Qc8 13. e3 {White wants to consolidate his position, the idea can be seen with 15.Nd3, the d4 pawn will be defended.} h6 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Ng4 (15. Nd3 {The role of 13.e3 - it defeded the d4 pawn.}) 15... Be7 16. f4 f5 (16... Qb7+ 17. Qf3 Qxf3+ 18. Kxf3 $14 {Generally, White wants to trade the queens and enter an endgame where White has a good knight against the bad dark-squared bishop on e7.}) 17. Ne5 Bf6 18. Qf3 Ra7 19. Rad1 Qe8 20. h4 Nb8 21. h5 Bxe5 22. dxe5 Qe7 23. e4 fxe4 24. Qxe4 Nc6 25. Qd3 Rf7 26. Qe3 Ra8 27. Rd3 Rf5 28. Nc5 Rd8 29. Rfd1 Nb8 30. g4 Rf7 31. Kg3 Rdf8 32. Rf1 Qe8 33. Rf2 Qe7 34. Rdd2 Qe8 35. Qe2 Qe7 36. Qe3 Qe8 37. Rf3 Qe7 38. Rd1 Qe8 39. Rd2 Qe7 40. Rd1 Qe8 41. Nd3 Nc6 42. Qe4 Qb8 43. Nc5 Qb6 44. Qe3 Nb8 45. Nd3 Nc6 46. Nc5 Nb8 47. Rd2 Re8 48. Nd3 Nc6 49. Qxb6 cxb6 50. Nf2 Ref8 51. Rdd3 Ra8 52. Ne4 a4 53. Nd6 Rff8 54. Nb5 Rfd8 55. Rd6 Kf8 56. Rfd3 Ke7 57. Nd4 axb3 58. axb3 Nxd4 59. R3xd4 Rab8 60. f5 b5 61. c5 Rbc8 62. c6 Rc7 63. Rxd7+ Rdxd7 64. Rxd7+ Rxd7 65. cxd7 Kxd7 66. Kf4 1-0

