1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 a6 4. Bg2 b5 5. b3 Bb7 6. Nc3 $1 {The positional approach after 5...Bb7. We play Nc3! provoking b5-b4 and creating weaknesses. This is a model game for this line!} b4 7. Na4 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. d4 d6 (9... a5 {Ulf Andersson played Bg5 here.} 10. Bg5 h6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. e3 Na6 13. Ne1 {Theoretically speaking, Black can keep the bishop pair but at a very high cost.} d5 $2 $16 {This is a strategically very bad move because a lot of squares on the c file will be weak, including the c7 pawn.}) 10. a3 a5 11. Bb2 c5 $6 {Now the c5 pawn will be weak after dxc5! and also the b6 square is weakened.} (11... Nbd7 12. d5 exd5 13. Nh4 Ne4 14. cxd5 Bxh4 15. Bxe4 Bf6 16. Bxf6 Nxf6 17. Bf3 $14) 12. dxc5 $1 (12. Qd2 Nbd7 13. dxc5 dxc5 14. Ne5 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Qc7 16. Nxd7 Nxd7 $14) 12... dxc5 {Sooner or later White should exchange the light-squared bishops.} 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. Rfd1 Nbd7 15. axb4 axb4 16. Ne5 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Rac8 (17... Nxe5 18. Bxe5 $14 {White's pieces are more active, the c5 pawn is weak and the b6 square is available for the knight (for example Nb6 Rxa1 Rxa1 and White can invade down the a-file). These factors give White a pleasant advantage.}) 18. Nxd7 Nxd7 19. Rd3 Nb8 20. Nb6 Rc6 (20... Rxd3 $4 21. Nxc8 $1 $18 Rd7 22. Nxe7+ (22. Ra8 $18) 22... Rxe7 23. Ra8 $18) 21. Ra7 Rxd3 22. exd3 Bd8 (22... Rxb6 23. Rxe7 Kf8 24. Rc7 Na6 25. Rc8+ Ke7 26. Bxg7 $18) 23. Na4 {This was a good example to see how much c5 was weak during this game and how the weakened b6 square was used.} f6 24. d4 cxd4 25. Bxd4 Bc7 26. Bc5 Na6 27. Bb6 1-0

