{This is another model game for white in the Romanishin line. You will see the 10.d5 idea in this variation.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 a6 4. Bg2 b5 5. b3 Bb7 6. Nc3 b4 7. Na4 Be7 8. Bb2 (8. O-O {I prefer Ulf Andersson's plan with d4, Bg5 and Bxf6!} O-O 9. d4 a5 10. Bg5) 8... d6 9. d4 O-O 10. d5 $5 {This is also an interesting idea for White.} exd5 11. Nh4 {[%cal Gc4d5,Gh4f5] White wants to take cxd5 and the pawn on c7 will be weak. That's why Black plays:} c5 {It's not the same c5 as in the previous examples as there we had the pawn on d4 and we took dxc5 dxc5 and the c5 pawn was weak. Here, it's protected from the d6 pawn.} 12. Nf5 Re8 13. cxd5 Bf8 14. Qd2 Bc8 15. Qg5 $14 {With a nice attacking position for White. White is better and he won later on.} Bxf5 16. Qxf5 Nbd7 17. Qc2 Qe7 18. e3 h5 19. O-O h4 20. e4 hxg3 21. hxg3 Ng4 22. Rae1 Qg5 23. f4 Qg6 24. Bf3 Nh6 25. Qh2 Rac8 26. Qh3 Re7 27. g4 f6 28. Re2 Qh7 29. g5 fxg5 30. fxg5 Nf7 31. Qxh7+ Kxh7 32. Bg4 Nxg5 33. Bxd7 Rxd7 34. Nb6 Rdd8 35. Nxc8 Rxc8 36. Bc1 Be7 37. Rf5 1-0

