{[%evp 0,17,21,20,47,18,18,4,2,-21,1,4,4,12,23,30,33,34,30,34]} 1. Nf3 {With extremely rare moves, sometimes it's better not to play the Reti and take bigger advantage immediately. The correct mentality is: - Play normal chess - take the center and develop your pieces!} c5 (1... b6 {Here, we can use the chance to play an open game without theory, or we can try and transpose to some line of the Reti most likely.} 2. e4 $1 {This is the correct move and the correct mentality! Even if you are not a 1.e4 player, this is not a classical 1.e4 opening.} (2. g3 Bb7 3. Bg2 {With this, it's most likely that sooner or later we will reach some Reti line. For example:} c5 4. b3 Nf6 5. Bb2 g6 6. c4 Bg7 7. O-O O-O {And this is the standard position where one good move is d4, and another good possibility is Nc3.}) 2... Bb7 3. Nc3 $14) (1... b5 $6 2. e4 Bb7 (2... a6 3. d4 {If here we simply control the center and we are better, it doesn't have to be Reti.} Bb7 4. Bd3) 3. Bxb5 Bxe4 4. d4 e6 5. O-O $16 Nf6 6. c4 a6 7. Ba4 Be7 8. Nc3 Bb7 9. Re1 $16 {[%cal Gc1f4,Ga4c2] White has a great position. This is a simple way to play against all these strange moves like 1...b5.}) (1... g6 {White can play many good moves such as e4, d4 or c4. Play normal chess - take the center and develop your pieces!} 2. e4 Bg7 3. d4) (1... Nc6 {Is a bit more serious since 2.e4 after 2...e5 will transpose to a normal e4 opening. After 2.c4 e5 will be an English version of the Reti, and in comparison, later on, we may not be able to put our bishop on b2 but instead, it may need to go on d2.} 2. d4 (2. e4 e5) 2... d5 3. g3 {Here, a better move would have been 3.c4 but 3.g3 is a Reti move order, for example: 1. Nf3-d5, 2.g3-Nc6, 3.d4 and we get the same position.}) (1... d5 2. g3 Nc6 3. d4 $1 $14 (3. Bg2 $6 {Be careful not to allow your opponent to gain space in the center!} e5)) (1... d6 {In these rare occasions where your opponent goes 1... d6, 2.g3 is fine but you can simply play 2.d4 and then g3, Bg2, get out of theory and play a normal game. This is again the same mentality that should be adopted against these rare moves.} 2. d4 (2. g3 {Is also playable and it is possible that it may become some version of the Reti.})) 2. c4 Nc6 {White can play 3.d4 or simply 3.b3} 3. b3 e5 4. Bb2 d6 {This is likely to transpose to some version of the positions that we have seen already.} (4... e4 5. Ng1 $14 {The Black pawn on e4 doesn't fit well with the c5 move.}) 5. d3 g6 6. g3 Bg7 7. Bg2 Nf6 (7... Nge7 {This might be possible for Black - The Botvinnik set-up.} 8. O-O O-O 9. Nc3 {The lines are similar - Nd2, a3, Rb1 and so on.}) 8. O-O O-O 9. Nc3 $14 *

